75
00:09:03,442 --> 00:09:05,672
My heart will never stand it, Herr Doctor.

76
00:09:06,846 --> 00:09:08,814
- Heart's fit.
- I have been under treatment for...

77
00:09:08,915 --> 00:09:10,906
Take him away. Next man.

78
00:09:11,017 --> 00:09:13,451
Karl Marsen, for insubordination.

79
00:09:13,553 --> 00:09:15,453
Sentence: 20 lashes.

80
00:09:15,555 --> 00:09:18,023
Good for twice the number by the look of him.

81
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:26,797
You will soon learn that it's
better to keep your mouth shut...

82
00:09:26,899 --> 00:09:28,799
and to do as you are told.

83
00:09:28,901 --> 00:09:32,428
Thank you. I have no wish to become a Nazi.

84
00:09:32,538 --> 00:09:35,507
We shall also teach you
that insolence does not pay.

85
00:09:35,608 --> 00:09:40,170
With the aid of those pillars of Nazi culture
- the whip and the jackboot.

86
00:09:40,279 --> 00:09:42,179
- Silence!
- I shall say what I like!

87
00:09:43,282 --> 00:09:45,182
You hate the truth...

88
00:09:45,284 --> 00:09:48,811
because, in the end, it will destroy
you and your bankrupt philosophy.

89
00:09:48,921 --> 00:09:52,322
You will perish because
you have nothing to offer...

90
00:09:52,425 --> 00:09:55,417
because you can't forever
replace tolerance and decency...

91
00:09:55,528 --> 00:09:58,088
with brute force, because you...

92
00:10:02,902 --> 00:10:04,597
<i>[Whip Strikes]</i>

93
00:10:11,444 --> 00:10:13,275
Stand away from him.

94
00:10:13,379 --> 00:10:15,347
<i>Get back to your work.</i>

95
00:10:16,515 --> 00:10:18,483
[Quietly] Better leave me.

96
00:10:23,789 --> 00:10:25,689
Mmm?

97
00:10:32,465 --> 00:10:34,433
Halt!

98
00:10:34,533 --> 00:10:36,558
Get along. No talking.

99
00:10:45,211 --> 00:10:46,906
Good Samaritan.

100
00:10:53,419 --> 00:10:56,320
I wanted to thank you for yesterday.

101
00:10:56,422 --> 00:10:58,049
The swine!

102
00:10:58,157 --> 00:11:00,591
Don't look at me. We shall be seen.

103
00:11:02,795 --> 00:11:04,695
Why did they send you here?

104
00:11:04,797 --> 00:11:06,697
Oh.

105
00:11:06,799 --> 00:11:08,767
I'm a desperate character.

106
00:11:09,969 --> 00:11:12,494
I had a little school on the Sudeten border.

107
00:11:12,605 --> 00:11:16,666
I was ordered to abolish our
language and to teach in German...

108
00:11:16,776 --> 00:11:19,540
by an illiterate Nazi group leader.

109
00:11:21,013 --> 00:11:22,913
So here I am.

110
00:11:23,015 --> 00:11:24,915
Shh.

111
00:11:31,857 --> 00:11:34,724
- And you?
- My father escaped to England.

112
00:11:35,828 --> 00:11:37,728
I almost went back with him.

113
00:11:37,830 --> 00:11:41,027
- Back?
- I was at school there.

114
00:11:41,133 --> 00:11:44,102
They arrested me to find
out where he was hiding...

115
00:11:44,203 --> 00:11:47,001
and because I couldn't tell them...

116
00:11:47,106 --> 00:11:49,006
That's all.

117
00:11:49,108 --> 00:11:50,735
England.

118
00:11:50,843 --> 00:11:52,811
Well, good luck to him.

119
00:11:54,880 --> 00:11:57,246
I have been a fool. I...

120
00:11:57,349 --> 00:11:59,817
I should have held my tongue and-and waited.

121
00:12:00,853 --> 00:12:03,447
- We shan't always be here.
- No?

122
00:12:04,490 --> 00:12:07,459
Somehow, I'm going to join my father.

123
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:09,027
How?

124
00:12:09,128 --> 00:12:12,928
- Well, we have friends outside.
- Yes.

125
00:12:13,032 --> 00:12:15,626
But between them and us...

126
00:12:15,735 --> 00:12:17,703
There must be a way.

127
00:12:18,738 --> 00:12:22,765
Past searchlights, machine guns, barbed wire?

128
00:12:24,710 --> 00:12:27,679
I should take any risk if I
thought there was a chance.

129
00:12:28,714 --> 00:12:30,614
But there is none.

130
00:12:32,084 --> 00:12:34,814
There isn't one of us
who doesn't lie awake...

131
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:37,013
- Keep your mouths shut!
- [Gasps]

132
00:12:37,123 --> 00:12:39,023
You know the order!

133
00:12:39,125 --> 00:12:41,025
Get back, you. I told...

134
00:12:51,570 --> 00:12:53,470
Silence.

135
00:12:56,609 --> 00:12:59,077
What is it? Do you know him?

136
00:13:00,212 --> 00:13:03,079
He studied with me for a
job in the civil bureau.

137
00:13:04,183 --> 00:13:05,810
He might help us.

138
00:13:05,918 --> 00:13:08,614
- But isn't he a German?
- Yes.

139
00:13:08,721 --> 00:13:10,712
From the Sudetenland.

140
00:13:10,823 --> 00:13:13,815
When it was occupied by
Germany, he was desperate.

141
00:13:13,926 --> 00:13:15,826
I gave him the advice.

142
00:13:15,928 --> 00:13:20,262
Become a good Nazi, Paul.
Join the party... and wait.

143
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:23,530
Then you think that...

144
00:13:23,636 --> 00:13:25,536
Yes.

145
00:13:25,638 --> 00:13:27,606
Now there may be a chance.

146
00:14:00,139 --> 00:14:03,734
- What's wrong up there?
- It's fused!

147
00:14:12,418 --> 00:14:14,784
It's all right!

148
00:14:36,709 --> 00:14:40,907
<i>[Alarm Ringing]</i>

149
00:14:50,055 --> 00:14:52,751
<i>[Ship Horn Blows]</i>

150
00:14:54,526 --> 00:14:56,653
- You should be asleep.
- Karl, what's that noise?

151
00:14:56,762 --> 00:15:00,163
- That's the Goodwin lightship, miss.
- We should be in England in an hour or two.

152
00:15:00,266 --> 00:15:02,166
But it'll be light then.

153
00:15:02,268 --> 00:15:05,294
You don't mean we're going ashore
without any passports in broad daylight?

154
00:15:05,404 --> 00:15:07,304
In broad daylight!

155
00:15:09,375 --> 00:15:12,003
<i>## [Brass Band]</i>

156
00:15:18,584 --> 00:15:21,178
<i>[Reople Chattering]</i>

157
00:15:21,287 --> 00:15:22,754
[Woman] Why not?

158
00:15:23,923 --> 00:15:25,823
Come on. Only a shilling.

159
00:15:25,925 --> 00:15:28,587
- Aye, aye, knock it. Turn it up.
What's the idea?
- Oh, I'm so sorry.

160
00:15:28,694 --> 00:15:31,720
<i>Think you're the Mauretania? I might have
had a Lillian Gish on the end of that.</i>

161
00:15:31,830 --> 00:15:35,266
- I'm very sorry indeed.
- All right. Granted, me ol' cock.

162
00:15:35,367 --> 00:15:37,597
- Have you caught anything?
- New eels.

163
00:15:37,703 --> 00:15:41,070
Oh! That's a night fish.
You've been out in a ketch.

164
00:15:41,173 --> 00:15:44,301
Not like me
- fishing to keep away from the old woman.

165
00:15:47,646 --> 00:15:49,546
- Where do we change?
- The beach.

166
00:15:49,648 --> 00:15:51,343
- And then London?
- Yes.

167
00:15:51,450 --> 00:15:53,418
There I shall go to see
a friend of my family.

168
00:15:53,519 --> 00:15:55,419
He fled to England last
September. He'll help us.

169
00:15:55,521 --> 00:15:57,489
He's living at a place called
Hampstead. You've heard of it?

170
00:15:57,589 --> 00:16:00,251
Yes. Karl, if you only knew
how glad I am to be back here...

171
00:16:00,359 --> 00:16:02,623
where people can still laugh and be happy.

172
00:16:02,728 --> 00:16:06,164
Come away, Alfie. If you're not falling
in something, you're dragging in something.

173
00:16:06,265 --> 00:16:08,165
Go on.

174
00:16:24,984 --> 00:16:26,884
- Good evening.
- Uh, good evening.

175
00:16:26,986 --> 00:16:29,386
- I should like to see Dr. Fredericks.
- Have you an appointment?

176
00:16:29,488 --> 00:16:33,686
No, but, uh, if you would give him
my name. It is Marsen. Karl Marsen.

177
00:16:33,792 --> 00:16:36,590
- Well, will you come in, please?
- Thank you.

178
00:16:44,269 --> 00:16:46,760
Now, if you will take this
to Gilby's, the opticians.

179
00:16:46,872 --> 00:16:48,772
They're just around the corner.

180
00:16:48,874 --> 00:16:52,332
If you mention my name, they will make up
your little girl's glasses at a reduced charge.

181
00:16:52,444 --> 00:16:54,036
Thank you, Doctor.

182
00:16:54,146 --> 00:16:56,580
And don't worry. With care,
she will grow out of it.

183
00:16:56,682 --> 00:16:58,650
- Thank you, Doctor. Good night.
- Good night.

184
00:16:58,751 --> 00:17:01,379
There's a gentleman to see
you, Doctor, a Mr. Marsen.

185
00:17:01,487 --> 00:17:03,182
Marsen?

186
00:17:03,288 --> 00:17:05,950
Oh, very well. Show him in.

187
00:17:07,059 --> 00:17:09,118
- The doctor will see you now.
- Thank you.

188
00:17:09,228 --> 00:17:11,128
Good luck.

189
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:15,258
Mr. Marsen.

190
00:17:15,367 --> 00:17:17,267
- Good evening.
- How do you do, Doctor?

191
00:17:17,369 --> 00:17:21,499
I was given your name. I'm suffering from
an, uh, eyestrain and should like a test.

192
00:17:21,607 --> 00:17:24,667
- Headaches and so forth?
- Hmm, yes.

193
00:17:24,777 --> 00:17:27,007
If you will be good enough
to sit in this chair, please?

194
00:17:27,112 --> 00:17:29,012
Thank you.

195
00:17:30,783 --> 00:17:33,217
- Warm this evening, isn't it?
- Rather.

196
00:17:36,922 --> 00:17:39,220
I hear there may be a storm brewing.

197
00:17:44,196 --> 00:17:47,654
Now, will you read the top line, please?

198
00:17:47,766 --> 00:17:50,792
K, M, S...

199
00:17:50,903 --> 00:17:54,464
Q, R, Y.

200
00:17:54,573 --> 00:17:56,803
And now the line underneath.

201
00:17:56,909 --> 00:18:00,140
M, O, 2...

202
00:18:00,245 --> 00:18:04,011
6, 7, 3, G.

203
00:18:04,116 --> 00:18:07,677
I don't think that is quite
right. Will you repeat it, please?

204
00:18:07,786 --> 00:18:11,153
M, O, 2...

205
00:18:11,256 --> 00:18:15,420
6, 7, 3, G.

206
00:18:36,682 --> 00:18:38,149
<i>- [Clicks Heels]
- Heil Hitler.</i>

207
00:18:38,250 --> 00:18:40,582
<i>- [Clicks Heels]
- Heil Hitler.</i>

208
00:18:40,686 --> 00:18:42,153
Well?

209
00:18:42,254 --> 00:18:45,746
I have to report that on instructions
from Gestapo headquarters...

210
00:18:45,858 --> 00:18:48,122
I successfully made contact
with the woman Bomasch...

211
00:18:48,227 --> 00:18:52,630
in Concentration Camp Number
Four, Reichsprotektorat of Bohemia.

212
00:18:52,731 --> 00:18:56,497
I escaped with her, as
arranged, on the 27 th ofJuly...

213
00:18:56,602 --> 00:19:01,062
<i>and came ashore this morning at
11:15, from the freighter Stovendam.</i>

214
00:19:01,173 --> 00:19:03,641
We are staying at an apartment house...

215
00:19:03,742 --> 00:19:07,508
at 124 Paddington Lane, Marylebone.

216
00:19:07,613 --> 00:19:11,481
Good. She has, of course, made
no attempt to locate her father.

217
00:19:11,583 --> 00:19:13,744
No. I am awaiting your instructions.

218
00:19:13,852 --> 00:19:15,752
This is all we know.

219
00:19:15,854 --> 00:19:19,381
Bomasch is working for the British
admiralty. Where, we have no idea.

220
00:19:19,491 --> 00:19:21,584
He is certainly well hidden and well guarded.

221
00:19:21,693 --> 00:19:24,924
- Therefore, we must move cautiously.
- Understood, sir.

222
00:19:25,030 --> 00:19:26,930
So do not appear too eager.

223
00:19:27,032 --> 00:19:30,490
Impress upon her that you are
aliens and must move carefully.

224
00:19:30,602 --> 00:19:35,198
Suggest that she places an
advertisement to this effect...

225
00:19:35,307 --> 00:19:38,333
<i>in the personal column of the London Times...</i>

226
00:19:38,443 --> 00:19:42,470
signed perhaps with some nickname
which her father will know at once.

227
00:19:42,581 --> 00:19:46,483
You will see that that advertisement
is repeated daily until it is answered.

228
00:19:46,585 --> 00:19:49,179
When that happens, you
will report to me instantly.

229
00:19:49,288 --> 00:19:51,188
- You understand?
- Yes, sir.

230
00:19:51,290 --> 00:19:52,848
<i>That is all. Heil Hitler.</i>

231
00:19:52,958 --> 00:19:55,426
<i>- [Clicks Heels]
- Heil Hitlerl</i>

232
00:19:57,262 --> 00:19:59,287
I see that fellow
Ribbentrop's going to Moscow.

233
00:19:59,398 --> 00:20:01,366
Hmm. So did Napoleon.

234
00:20:11,076 --> 00:20:13,271
<i>[Woman] Miss Bomasch,
you're wanted on the phone.</i>

235
00:20:13,378 --> 00:20:15,471
<i>Nice time of night to ring up, I must say.</i>

236
00:20:15,581 --> 00:20:17,879
<i>- [Anna] Who is it?
- Oh, he didn't say.</i>

237
00:20:19,484 --> 00:20:21,384
<i>[Footsteps]</i>

238
00:20:25,624 --> 00:20:28,491
Hello? Yes, I'm Anna Bomasch.

239
00:20:28,594 --> 00:20:30,960
<i>In the Times, yes. Who is it?</i>

240
00:20:31,063 --> 00:20:32,963
Yes, I'm alone. Who is it, please?

241
00:20:33,065 --> 00:20:36,933
I can't answer questions.
Now please listen carefully.

242
00:20:37,035 --> 00:20:39,868
At the post office in Prairie
Street, a letter is waiting for you...

243
00:20:39,972 --> 00:20:41,872
containing a railway ticket.

244
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:44,841
Go to the destination on the ticket,
and when you get to the town...

245
00:20:44,943 --> 00:20:46,934
ask for a man named Gus Bennett.

246
00:20:48,046 --> 00:20:50,310
You've got the name? Gus Bennett.

247
00:20:50,415 --> 00:20:53,384
- Yes, but who do I ask?
- Everyone there knows Gus Bennett.

248
00:20:53,485 --> 00:20:56,454
You say nothing of this to
anyone. That is most important.

249
00:20:58,557 --> 00:21:00,525
Hello?

250
00:21:00,626 --> 00:21:02,526
Hello!

251
00:21:12,904 --> 00:21:14,804
<i>[Knocking]</i>

252
00:21:16,041 --> 00:21:18,509
<i>- Yes?
- It's Anna. May I come in?</i>

253
00:21:18,610 --> 00:21:20,510
Yes, come in.

254
00:21:21,546 --> 00:21:23,980
Karl, I've just heard. Somebody telephoned.

255
00:21:24,082 --> 00:21:25,982
- We found him.
- Where?

256
00:21:26,084 --> 00:21:29,076
- I don't know yet.
- But, uh, what did he say?

257
00:21:29,187 --> 00:21:32,987
Karl, I'd love to tell you, but whoever it
was said I wasn't to say a word to anyone.

258
00:21:33,091 --> 00:21:35,286
- Oh.
- I don't mean you're just anyone.

259
00:21:35,394 --> 00:21:38,261
- Of course you're not, but...
- Anna, I...

260
00:21:38,363 --> 00:21:40,490
I would much rather you didn't tell me.

261
00:21:40,599 --> 00:21:45,366
We don't know what your father is doing, and
it's probably right you should take precautions.

262
00:21:45,470 --> 00:21:48,564
There's no one in the
world I'd rather confide in.

263
00:21:48,674 --> 00:21:51,643
I don't know what I'd have
done if it hadn't been for you.

264
00:21:51,743 --> 00:21:53,643
No.

265
00:21:55,580 --> 00:21:57,707
- You are happy now?
- Mm-hmm.

266
00:22:00,385 --> 00:22:03,684
Well, that's all that matters.

267
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:06,890
Good night, Karl.

268
00:22:17,069 --> 00:22:19,196
<i>[Telegraph Clicking]</i>

269
00:22:30,882 --> 00:22:32,850
[Horn Honking]

270
00:22:34,152 --> 00:22:37,883
<i>- ## [Man Singing]
- I'm looking for Mr. Gus Bennett.
I was told I'd find him here.</i>

271
00:22:37,989 --> 00:22:39,889
Oh, he's along here, all right.

272
00:22:39,991 --> 00:22:42,789
You hear a warbling note like an air
raid siren? Well, that's him singing.

273
00:22:42,894 --> 00:22:45,454
<i>- # Only love can cheer the day #
- Over there?</i>

274
00:22:45,564 --> 00:22:48,226
<i>[Man] Churns out the same moldy
songs from 9:00 in the morning.</i>

275
00:22:48,333 --> 00:22:50,563
A human barrel organ, he is.

276
00:22:50,669 --> 00:22:54,435
- # Lots in life may be denied #
- ## [Piano]

277
00:22:54,539 --> 00:22:57,099
# But hearts can laugh #

278
00:22:57,209 --> 00:22:58,938
<i># When love's inside #</i>

279
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:03,174
<i># For only love can lead the way #</i>

280
00:23:03,281 --> 00:23:09,151
# As time rolls on and on ##

281
00:23:09,254 --> 00:23:11,154
The song of the century!

282
00:23:11,256 --> 00:23:14,123
When "Home Sweet Home" and "Annie Laurie"
are forgotten, this song will live on.

283
00:23:14,226 --> 00:23:16,558
Now, madam, only the
price of a stick of rock.

284
00:23:16,661 --> 00:23:20,153
Sixpence, sir. The ballad of the age.
"Only Love Can Lead the Way".

285
00:23:20,265 --> 00:23:22,756
Here, buy a copy for the sergeant
major. Thank you, gentlemen! Thank you!

286
00:23:22,868 --> 00:23:24,961
Anyone else want to buy a
copy of this haunting melody?

287
00:23:25,070 --> 00:23:27,129
How would you like to be
haunted for a sixpence, miss?

288
00:23:27,239 --> 00:23:29,605
- Mr. Gus Bennett?
- In the flesh. You want me to autograph it?
I'll throw that in.

289
00:23:29,708 --> 00:23:31,335
- I'm Anna Bomasch.
- How do you do?

290
00:23:31,443 --> 00:23:33,775
Don't go away, ladies and gentlemen!
I'm not gonna sing again yet.

291
00:23:33,879 --> 00:23:36,245
- I was told to come and see you, Mr. Bennett.
- Hmm? Who by?

292
00:23:36,348 --> 00:23:38,475
- I don't know.
- Is this a gag?

293
00:23:38,583 --> 00:23:41,347
Well, somebody phoned me. They
said you'd have news of my father.

294
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:43,478
Your father? Never heard of
him. Somebody's pulling your leg.

295
00:23:43,588 --> 00:23:45,886
"Only Love Can Lead the Way".
A tonic so far.

296
00:23:45,991 --> 00:23:47,891
We give the tonic.
You provide the "so far".

297
00:23:47,993 --> 00:23:50,621
Thank you, madam. Hey, don't go away.
I'm just going to tear off another number.

298
00:23:50,729 --> 00:23:52,196
Then we'll have a talk.

299
00:23:52,297 --> 00:23:54,390
I'm now going to sing the
sentimental song hit of the year.

300
00:23:54,499 --> 00:23:56,763
They say the hand that rocks
the cradle rules the world...

301
00:23:56,868 --> 00:24:00,065
but, believe me, it's songs
like this that fill it.

302
00:24:00,172 --> 00:24:02,140
# It's true #

303
00:24:02,240 --> 00:24:05,073
# Oh, what it does to me to know it's true #

304
00:24:05,177 --> 00:24:07,077
# She loves me ##

305
00:24:07,179 --> 00:24:11,206
[Slurping] Are you... Are you sure
it was Gus Bennett they said?

306
00:24:11,316 --> 00:24:13,750
- Yes, I'm certain.
- Your father's not in the song business?

307
00:24:13,852 --> 00:24:16,412
- No.
- Well, it's beyond me. How did you lose him?

308
00:24:16,521 --> 00:24:19,251
- He escaped.
- Escaped? You mean he's still at large?

309
00:24:19,357 --> 00:24:21,621
- I-I mean, you haven't seen him since?
- No.

310
00:24:21,726 --> 00:24:23,626
You see, I was in a concentration camp.

311
00:24:23,728 --> 00:24:26,094
- Were you really? Where?
- Near Prague.

312
00:24:26,198 --> 00:24:28,098
Prague.

313
00:24:29,301 --> 00:24:31,201
- You here by yourself?
- Yes.

314
00:24:31,303 --> 00:24:34,067
- Anyone know you're here?
- No.

315
00:24:34,172 --> 00:24:36,834
- Would you like another one of these?
- No, thank you.

316
00:24:37,943 --> 00:24:40,070
<i>[Woman] Alfie?</i>

317
00:24:40,178 --> 00:24:42,078
I don't understand it. It's extraordinary.

318
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:44,478
Well, it amounts to this.
You don't know my father...

319
00:24:44,583 --> 00:24:47,347
you don't know anything about
him, and you can't help me.

320
00:24:47,452 --> 00:24:49,420
Is that him?

321
00:25:04,135 --> 00:25:06,035
Father!

322
00:25:06,137 --> 00:25:08,605
Anna!

323
00:25:27,158 --> 00:25:30,491
Here it is
- Brightbourne, a health resort.

324
00:25:30,595 --> 00:25:33,291
But I hardly think that Herr
Bomasch is there for his health.

325
00:25:33,398 --> 00:25:36,492
You notice across the bay
is the Dartland naval base.

326
00:25:36,601 --> 00:25:39,229
Reports says he's been there
three times in the last week.

327
00:25:39,337 --> 00:25:41,305
Probably conducting experiments, sir.

328
00:25:41,406 --> 00:25:43,397
Precisely. We can't afford
to delay a moment longer.

329
00:25:43,508 --> 00:25:45,408
There's another reason for haste.

330
00:25:45,510 --> 00:25:48,377
Any day now, Poland may provoke us
into invading her in self-defense.

331
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:50,380
England will not stand by Poland.

332
00:25:50,482 --> 00:25:52,950
We have the personal assurance
of Herr von Ribbentrop as to that.

333
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:54,951
Hmm. So I understand.

334
00:25:55,053 --> 00:25:59,046
Nevertheless, instruct Fredericks that we
are putting arrangements in hand at once.

335
00:25:59,157 --> 00:26:01,057
Very good, sir.

336
00:26:02,761 --> 00:26:04,752
# You nonchalantly go around #

337
00:26:04,863 --> 00:26:06,763
# Completely unaware #

338
00:26:06,865 --> 00:26:09,060
# It's just another ordinary day #

339
00:26:10,402 --> 00:26:13,963
# You meet a sweet who
sweeps you off your feet #

340
00:26:14,072 --> 00:26:17,940
# Your heart skips a beat and runs away #

341
00:26:18,043 --> 00:26:21,774
# You can't recall a tender
thought to show how much you care #

342
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:25,680
<i># You can't think of a single thing to say #</i>

343
00:26:25,784 --> 00:26:29,345
# You'll meet, so meek You'll
talk, but you don't speak #

344
00:26:29,454 --> 00:26:32,890
# Your heart skips a beat and runs away #

345
00:26:32,991 --> 00:26:35,425
# It may be Tuesday or Sunday #

346
00:26:35,527 --> 00:26:37,552
# Thursday or Monday #

347
00:26:37,662 --> 00:26:40,187
<i># Love never warns you at all #</i>

348
00:26:40,298 --> 00:26:42,858
- Is the coffee ready?
- It won't be a minute.

349
00:26:42,968 --> 00:26:44,936
<i>- Thank you, dear.
- ## [Woman Continues, Indistinct]</i>

350
00:26:45,036 --> 00:26:46,936
<i>- [Door Opens]
- Oh, hello.</i>

351
00:26:47,038 --> 00:26:49,165
- Hello there.
- Come to see Father?

352
00:26:49,274 --> 00:26:51,174
No.

353
00:26:53,244 --> 00:26:55,212
- Want some?
- Thank you.

354
00:26:59,951 --> 00:27:02,920
- Where did you get that from?
- Post office stopped it.

355
00:27:03,021 --> 00:27:05,319
- Why?
- I gave them instructions.

356
00:27:05,423 --> 00:27:08,017
What have my private letters to do with you?

357
00:27:08,126 --> 00:27:10,117
A postmark's a dangerous thing.

358
00:27:10,228 --> 00:27:12,890
- This letter's to a friend of mine.
- British?

359
00:27:12,998 --> 00:27:14,625
- No.
- Refugee?

360
00:27:14,733 --> 00:27:17,361
I'm not going to be cross-examined.

361
00:27:17,469 --> 00:27:21,633
I must remind you that the government
pay me a wage -small but regular-
to look after your father.

362
00:27:21,740 --> 00:27:23,640
It's obviously not small enough.

363
00:27:23,742 --> 00:27:26,210
You don't suppose I'd write
to anybody I couldn't trust.

364
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:28,245
Why, if it wasn't for
Karl, I wouldn't be here.

365
00:27:28,346 --> 00:27:30,246
What did you say?

366
00:27:30,348 --> 00:27:32,873
- He escaped with me.
- But you never told me.

367
00:27:32,984 --> 00:27:35,612
- I told my father.
- But not me.

368
00:27:35,720 --> 00:27:38,917
If I didn't, it's simply because
Karl is an alien without a passport.

369
00:27:39,024 --> 00:27:41,618
He was afraid he might be deported.

370
00:27:44,496 --> 00:27:48,193
- Known him long?
- No. What are you doing?

371
00:27:48,299 --> 00:27:50,324
Just want to check up on him.

372
00:27:50,435 --> 00:27:52,335
Have you ever heard of an organized escape?

373
00:27:52,437 --> 00:27:55,634
<i>- Organized?
- To lead them to your father.</i>

374
00:27:55,740 --> 00:27:59,232
But that's fantastic. Karl
doesn't even know where I am.

375
00:27:59,344 --> 00:28:01,209
Are you sure of that?

376
00:28:01,312 --> 00:28:03,576
- Of course. I told no one.
- Good.

377
00:28:03,682 --> 00:28:06,150
Honestly, I don't want to throw
a monkey wrench into the romance.

378
00:28:06,251 --> 00:28:10,483
Thank you. I appreciate that you're
inspired by the highest motives...

379
00:28:10,588 --> 00:28:12,556
and that you'll go to any
lengths to pursue them.

380
00:28:12,657 --> 00:28:16,024
- Any lengths.
- Even to exhibiting yourself
in public as a singer.

381
00:28:16,127 --> 00:28:18,994
Well, nature endowed me with a gift,
and I just accepted it. That's all.

382
00:28:19,097 --> 00:28:21,224
It's a pity it didn't endow you with a voice.

383
00:28:21,332 --> 00:28:23,527
Nothing that happened to me
in that concentration camp...

384
00:28:23,635 --> 00:28:26,103
was quite as dreadful as
listening to you day after day...

385
00:28:26,204 --> 00:28:28,104
singing those appalling songs.

386
00:28:28,206 --> 00:28:31,505
<i>With those few words, you've knocked
the bottom out of my entire existence.</i>

387
00:28:31,609 --> 00:28:33,577
A pity I only knocked it.

388
00:28:36,548 --> 00:28:38,539
<i>[Knocking]</i>

389
00:28:38,650 --> 00:28:40,982
<i>- Mr. Bomasch about?
- Yes, he is.</i>

390
00:28:41,086 --> 00:28:42,986
Admiral Baldwin sends his compliments.

391
00:28:43,088 --> 00:28:45,283
He'd like Mr. Bomasch to have
dinner with him this evening.

392
00:28:45,390 --> 00:28:47,358
- And his daughter.
- Hmm. I'll tell him.

393
00:28:49,794 --> 00:28:53,992
Uh, just a minute. Didn't Admiral Baldwin
leave for the Mediterranean last Tuesday?

394
00:28:54,099 --> 00:28:57,296
<i>No. He's aboard the
flagship lying off Dartland.</i>

395
00:28:57,402 --> 00:28:59,370
- But I understood that...
- [Blow Lands]

396
00:29:04,042 --> 00:29:05,566
<i>[Motor Chugging]</i>

397
00:29:12,917 --> 00:29:15,215
Isn't he going too far out for Dartland?

398
00:29:50,488 --> 00:29:52,615
<i>[Man Speaking German]</i>

399
00:29:52,724 --> 00:29:55,192
<i>[Man #2 Speaking German]</i>

400
00:30:19,884 --> 00:30:22,512
<i>[Bell Chiming]</i>

401
00:30:27,158 --> 00:30:30,616
<i>[Bell Tolling]</i>

402
00:30:34,899 --> 00:30:38,960
Sorry to barge in. I say,
Charles, the wife's just phoned.

403
00:30:39,070 --> 00:30:42,403
- I understand you're coming over
to tea on Sunday.
- Yes, so I believe.

404
00:30:42,507 --> 00:30:45,635
Well, she wants you to remind
Beryl to bring some recipe book-

405
00:30:45,743 --> 00:30:47,643
pickling walnuts or something.

406
00:30:47,745 --> 00:30:50,043
- Oh, yes. Will do.
- Right.

407
00:30:51,683 --> 00:30:54,174
- Oh, hello, Randall. How are you?
- Hello. Hi.

408
00:30:54,285 --> 00:30:56,583
We were just discussing the Bomasch affair.

409
00:30:56,688 --> 00:30:58,883
Oh, yes, you slipped up
rather badly there, didn't you?

410
00:30:58,990 --> 00:31:00,958
- Yes, I...
- Well, it wasn't exactly his fault.

411
00:31:01,059 --> 00:31:03,027
We ought to have known about Karl Marsen.

412
00:31:03,127 --> 00:31:05,027
The War Office has been stinking about him.

413
00:31:05,129 --> 00:31:07,324
They take the view that this
armor plating of Bomasch's...

414
00:31:07,432 --> 00:31:09,832
will make all the difference in the next war.

415
00:31:09,934 --> 00:31:12,459
Probably nothing of the sort,
but, well, there you are.

416
00:31:12,570 --> 00:31:14,731
And by tonight, Bomasch will be in Berlin...

417
00:31:14,839 --> 00:31:18,707
where they won't lose any time before
putting the screws on the poor devil.

418
00:31:18,810 --> 00:31:21,142
Tomorrow night?

419
00:31:21,246 --> 00:31:25,182
That means he won't be
at the admiralty until, let's see
- Saturday morning.

420
00:31:25,283 --> 00:31:27,615
That's about it. Why?

421
00:31:27,719 --> 00:31:29,914
Twenty-four, maybe 48 hours.

422
00:31:30,021 --> 00:31:31,921
Why? What are you driving at?

423
00:31:32,023 --> 00:31:35,254
Well, they got him out of England.
Why shouldn't I get him back?

424
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:38,625
But that's quite impossible.

425
00:31:38,730 --> 00:31:41,597
Why? I know my way about.
I was three years in Berlin.

426
00:31:41,699 --> 00:31:45,294
<i>- Drinking lager.
- Mmm. Vodka now, isn't it?</i>

427
00:31:45,403 --> 00:31:47,303
What about the Polish situation?

428
00:31:47,405 --> 00:31:49,930
Germany may march at any
moment. You know what that means.

429
00:31:50,041 --> 00:31:52,805
I shall be back before then. Well, sir?

430
00:31:54,846 --> 00:31:57,872
Well, you know perfectly well I
can't give you permission to do it.

431
00:31:57,982 --> 00:32:00,917
And the fact that you make the request
at all shows you're not yourself.

432
00:32:01,019 --> 00:32:02,987
- Don't you think so, Gaskin?
- Oh, well, I...

433
00:32:03,087 --> 00:32:04,884
I quite agree with you.

434
00:32:04,989 --> 00:32:06,957
Now, I suggest you take
a week's sick leave...

435
00:32:07,058 --> 00:32:09,686
to enable you to get a
complete change of air, hmm?

436
00:32:09,794 --> 00:32:12,922
Thank you, sir. I understand. I think
it might be very good for both of us.

437
00:32:13,031 --> 00:32:15,727
Mm-hmm. Now, I expect you'd like
to have a little chat about it.

438
00:32:15,833 --> 00:32:17,733
Yes, I would, sir.

439
00:32:17,835 --> 00:32:20,736
Oh, well, uh, Charles, you won't
forget about that recipe, will you?

440
00:32:20,838 --> 00:32:23,238
No, no. I'll remember.

441
00:32:23,341 --> 00:32:25,332
Now look here. I don't
know what your plans are...

442
00:32:25,443 --> 00:32:27,468
but I expect you'll want a
few letters of introduction.

443
00:32:27,578 --> 00:32:29,205
Mm-hmm.

444
00:32:33,952 --> 00:32:37,183
[Horns Honking]

445
00:32:40,391 --> 00:32:42,484
<i>[Horn Honking]</i>

446
00:32:44,028 --> 00:32:47,520
[Man] Reichssender Königs
Wusterhausen calling.

447
00:32:47,632 --> 00:32:52,092
Early this morning, the
Polish hoards attacked Germany.

448
00:32:52,203 --> 00:32:57,937
<i>The führer immediately gave orders to
our glorious army to invade Roland...</i>

449
00:32:58,042 --> 00:33:00,772
<i>and to destroy these
intolerable aggressors...</i>

450
00:33:00,878 --> 00:33:02,846
<i>of peace-loving Germany.</i>

451
00:33:11,122 --> 00:33:13,090
<i>Naval High Command, Herr Major.</i>

452
00:33:13,191 --> 00:33:15,159
- How can I reach you?
- I'll ring you tonight.

453
00:33:15,259 --> 00:33:17,227
I'll be waiting. Good luck.

454
00:33:23,501 --> 00:33:25,867
All identity cards.

455
00:33:27,638 --> 00:33:29,572
All identity cards.

456
00:33:30,908 --> 00:33:33,035
<i>All identity cards to be shown.</i>

457
00:33:33,144 --> 00:33:35,112
All identity cards.

458
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:38,908
<i>All identity cards to be shown.</i>

459
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:44,818
Identity card? Come on, come on, come on.

460
00:33:44,922 --> 00:33:47,447
I've worked here for 10 years. You
Gestapo fellows must want a job.

461
00:33:47,558 --> 00:33:49,583
- All right, all right.
- This is a fine country to live in.

462
00:33:49,694 --> 00:33:51,924
- Hey. What's that?
- Nothing.

463
00:33:52,030 --> 00:33:55,397
- Name. Department.
- Schwab. Records. Intelligence.

464
00:33:57,035 --> 00:33:59,128
- Report that man.
- Excellent, Officer.

465
00:33:59,237 --> 00:34:02,331
While we have men like you at home,
we have nothing to fear. Nothing.

466
00:34:03,541 --> 00:34:05,509
Oh, I have an appointment
with Commander Kampfeldt.

467
00:34:05,610 --> 00:34:07,771
- Where can I find him?
- Second floor, sir.

468
00:34:07,879 --> 00:34:09,403
Thank you.

469
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:14,610
This is a very grave matter, very grave.

470
00:34:14,719 --> 00:34:17,483
It has just been reported to me that
you've been heard expressing sentiments...

471
00:34:17,588 --> 00:34:19,215
hostile to the fatherland.

472
00:34:19,323 --> 00:34:20,950
- What, me, sir?
- What is it?

473
00:34:21,059 --> 00:34:23,459
Major Herzoff to see you.
He asked me to give you this.

474
00:34:23,561 --> 00:34:26,121
Can't you see I'm engaged?

475
00:34:26,230 --> 00:34:29,825
I warn you, Schwab, such treasonable conduct
will lead you to a concentration camp.

476
00:34:29,934 --> 00:34:31,834
But, sir, what did I say?

477
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:35,235
You were distinctly heard to remark,
"This is a fine country to live in".

478
00:34:35,339 --> 00:34:37,307
Oh, no, sir. There's some mistake.

479
00:34:37,408 --> 00:34:41,139
<i>No, what I said was,
"This is a fine country to live in".</i>

480
00:34:41,245 --> 00:34:43,145
Huh?

481
00:34:43,247 --> 00:34:44,874
- You sure?
- Yes, sir.

482
00:34:44,982 --> 00:34:47,246
Hmm. I see.

483
00:34:47,351 --> 00:34:50,411
Well, in future, don't make
remarks that can be taken two ways.

484
00:34:50,521 --> 00:34:53,115
- Much wiser not to talk politics at all.
- Yes, sir.

485
00:34:53,224 --> 00:34:54,748
<i>- You may go.
- Heil Hitler.</i>

486
00:34:54,859 --> 00:34:56,759
<i>Heil Hitler.</i>

487
00:35:02,733 --> 00:35:04,724
<i>This is a fine country to live in.</i>

488
00:35:06,771 --> 00:35:09,137
<i>This is a fine country to live in.</i>

489
00:35:11,242 --> 00:35:14,211
This is a bloody awful country to live in.

490
00:35:14,312 --> 00:35:16,439
Shall I show Major Herzoff in, sir?

491
00:35:16,547 --> 00:35:19,539
- Uh, yes, yes.
- Yes, sir.

492
00:35:19,650 --> 00:35:21,413
Please.

493
00:35:22,453 --> 00:35:24,353
Major Herzoff.

494
00:35:25,389 --> 00:35:27,016
<i>- Heil Hitler.
- Heil Hitler.</i>

495
00:35:27,125 --> 00:35:28,752
- Sit down, Major.
- Thank you.

496
00:35:28,860 --> 00:35:30,828
Sorry to keep you waiting.

497
00:35:32,530 --> 00:35:35,556
"This is to introduce to
you Major Ulrich Herzoff...

498
00:35:35,666 --> 00:35:37,566
"of the Corps of Engineers.

499
00:35:37,668 --> 00:35:41,104
"Major Herzoff is in Berlin on
an important technical mission...

500
00:35:41,205 --> 00:35:44,333
"for which he requires admiralty assistance.

501
00:35:44,442 --> 00:35:49,311
"I am sure, my dear Kampfeldt, that
you will give him your best cooperation.

502
00:35:49,413 --> 00:35:52,405
<i>Heil Hitler. " Et cetera,
et cetera, et cetera.</i>

503
00:35:52,517 --> 00:35:55,680
I wish these War Office fellows
would learn to write properly.

504
00:35:55,786 --> 00:35:57,686
Signature might be anything.

505
00:35:57,788 --> 00:36:00,086
Whose is it?

506
00:36:00,191 --> 00:36:02,159
Well, I have no idea.

507
00:36:02,260 --> 00:36:04,660
As usual, I was taken
from one office to another.

508
00:36:04,762 --> 00:36:07,595
- I suppose it couldn't be Sardvitz.
- Sardvitz?

509
00:36:07,698 --> 00:36:09,666
Or did he go in the purge?

510
00:36:09,767 --> 00:36:12,292
- I can't remember.
- I believe he did.

511
00:36:12,403 --> 00:36:15,895
Hmm. Whoever he was, he
spoke very highly of you.

512
00:36:16,007 --> 00:36:17,907
He did?

513
00:36:18,009 --> 00:36:20,409
Might be Meidvidtz.

514
00:36:20,511 --> 00:36:22,479
Not very likely though.

515
00:36:22,580 --> 00:36:25,743
However, the important thing
is, what can I do for you?

516
00:36:25,850 --> 00:36:28,284
I want to refer to certain
technical evidence...

517
00:36:28,386 --> 00:36:31,878
given before the Naval Heavy
Armaments 1935 Committee.

518
00:36:31,989 --> 00:36:34,389
If you will let me have a
report of the copy, Commander.

519
00:36:34,492 --> 00:36:38,929
Certainly. It will take only a moment.
I have my own filing system here.

520
00:36:39,964 --> 00:36:44,458
A copy of the Naval Heavy
Armaments 1935 Committee's report.

521
00:36:46,737 --> 00:36:48,967
- Have you been in Berlin long, Major?
- No.

522
00:36:49,073 --> 00:36:51,303
I only left the Siegfried line last Tuesday.

523
00:36:51,409 --> 00:36:53,604
Really? How is it there?

524
00:36:53,711 --> 00:36:56,009
Things are pretty hectic, I expect.

525
00:36:57,048 --> 00:36:59,016
Pumping night and day.

526
00:37:00,418 --> 00:37:03,216
I was there in a consultative capacity.

527
00:37:03,321 --> 00:37:06,779
Steel fortifications.
You possibly have heard.

528
00:37:06,891 --> 00:37:10,088
<i>Oh, yes, yes. Major Herzoff, of course.</i>

529
00:37:12,663 --> 00:37:14,927
Looks rather like Stuckner.

530
00:37:15,032 --> 00:37:17,933
But I believe he is doing
diplomatic work in the Balkans.

531
00:37:18,035 --> 00:37:20,833
<i>- And who is not?
- [Door Opens]</i>

532
00:37:20,938 --> 00:37:24,305
I'm afraid we haven't a
copy of the 1935 report, sir.

533
00:37:24,408 --> 00:37:27,377
- What's that?
- We have one of'34, but not '35.

534
00:37:27,478 --> 00:37:29,946
Are you sure there was a '35 committee?

535
00:37:30,047 --> 00:37:32,106
I sat in it myself as army liaison officer.

536
00:37:32,216 --> 00:37:35,982
I beg your pardon. Very well, very well.

537
00:37:36,087 --> 00:37:39,386
It's these fellows at the top.
They forget to send copies on.

538
00:37:39,490 --> 00:37:42,482
Perhaps the construction
department might be able to help.

539
00:37:42,593 --> 00:37:45,790
The very thing. They might have
one. I'll ring them at once.

540
00:37:45,896 --> 00:37:48,057
- Oh, I'm sorry...
- No trouble at all.

541
00:37:48,165 --> 00:37:50,065
Commander Prada.

542
00:37:50,167 --> 00:37:54,297
I have with me Major Ulrich
Herzoff of the Corps of Engineers.

543
00:37:54,405 --> 00:37:58,705
He is well known for his splendid
technical achievements on our west wall...

544
00:37:58,809 --> 00:38:01,107
as you're no doubt aware.

545
00:38:01,212 --> 00:38:05,342
<i>He will be greatly obliged if
you can give him some assistance.</i>

546
00:38:05,449 --> 00:38:08,316
You'll see him at once? Thank you, sir.

547
00:38:12,890 --> 00:38:16,087
1935, you said. I guess I could
get hold of a copy for you.

548
00:38:16,193 --> 00:38:19,060
Now, Commander Prada, you may
be able to help me more directly.

549
00:38:19,163 --> 00:38:21,131
- You know, I just left the Siegfried line.
- Mm-hmm.

550
00:38:21,232 --> 00:38:24,599
- So Kampfeldt said. How is everything?
- The Krupp's armor plating is the trouble.

551
00:38:24,702 --> 00:38:27,296
Confidentially, that's why I am in Berlin.

552
00:38:27,405 --> 00:38:31,000
Do you realize that the steel used by the
Czechs is better than anything we have got?

553
00:38:31,108 --> 00:38:34,441
Mm-hmm. So I've heard. But surely,
now that we control the Harska works...

554
00:38:34,545 --> 00:38:37,810
Not enough. We let the only man who
counted there slip through our fingers.

555
00:38:37,915 --> 00:38:40,577
- Bomasch.
- Yes. I knew Axel Bomasch personally.

556
00:38:40,685 --> 00:38:43,677
I was present at the first gunnery test
of his G.K. plating. Incredible results.

557
00:38:43,788 --> 00:38:45,688
Where is he? Working for Britain.

558
00:38:45,790 --> 00:38:48,418
<i>But if we can't trace this 1935 report-</i>

559
00:38:48,526 --> 00:38:52,986
One moment, Major. You will be surprised to
hear that Bomasch is no longer in England.

560
00:38:53,097 --> 00:38:54,394
What?

561
00:38:54,498 --> 00:38:57,262
He was brought back to
Germany only a few hours ago.

562
00:38:57,368 --> 00:38:59,495
<i>In fact, he's in this building now.</i>

563
00:39:08,946 --> 00:39:11,608
But this completely alters my plans.

564
00:39:11,716 --> 00:39:14,184
Perhaps you can arrange for
me to see Herr Bomasch at once.

565
00:39:14,285 --> 00:39:16,253
I'm afraid it's impossible.
He's with the controller.

566
00:39:16,354 --> 00:39:18,652
Surely there's no harm in my
asking him a few questions.

567
00:39:18,756 --> 00:39:20,724
It's beyond my province, Major.

568
00:39:20,825 --> 00:39:24,226
I'll pass you on to Captain Viengarten,
but frankly I don't think
it will get you any further.

569
00:39:24,328 --> 00:39:26,387
The controller's office is rather
like the kingdom of heaven...

570
00:39:26,497 --> 00:39:29,091
and, if anything, a little more exclusive.

571
00:39:30,134 --> 00:39:32,728
But you are no longer living
in a decadent democracy...

572
00:39:32,837 --> 00:39:35,032
ruled by a pack of raving intellectuals!

573
00:39:35,139 --> 00:39:38,165
This is the Third Reich, and
the führer does not tolerate...

574
00:39:38,275 --> 00:39:40,800
stupid, insolent obstinacy!

575
00:39:40,911 --> 00:39:43,641
You have been asked to work for
Germany, Herr Bomasch, and you will.

576
00:39:43,748 --> 00:39:47,047
Can't you leave him alone? You've bullied
and shouted at him ever since we got here!

577
00:39:47,151 --> 00:39:49,051
- He's had no sleep!
- He must agree!

578
00:39:51,088 --> 00:39:53,454
Can I have another word with him, sir?

579
00:39:53,557 --> 00:39:55,457
As you please.

580
00:40:01,732 --> 00:40:05,634
Anna. It's useless for your
father to resist like this.

581
00:40:05,736 --> 00:40:09,035
You must persuade him. You will
both be given reasonable freedom.

582
00:40:09,140 --> 00:40:11,040
Freedom here?

583
00:40:11,142 --> 00:40:13,508
In time, you will see things the way I do...

584
00:40:13,611 --> 00:40:16,011
the way everyone in Germany does.

585
00:40:16,113 --> 00:40:18,013
I'm not a German.

586
00:40:18,115 --> 00:40:21,676
Germany is as much your
country as it is ours now.

587
00:40:21,786 --> 00:40:24,584
We don't hate the Czechs.
We only wish to protect them.

588
00:40:24,688 --> 00:40:26,918
As you're protecting the people of Poland?

589
00:40:27,024 --> 00:40:30,084
You have been too long in Britain,
listening to their smug hypocrisy!

590
00:40:30,194 --> 00:40:34,062
If I listened to hypocrisy in
Britain, it was not from the British.

591
00:40:37,168 --> 00:40:39,636
I was doing my duty...

592
00:40:39,737 --> 00:40:43,696
as a citizen of the Reich
and a subject of the führer...

593
00:40:43,808 --> 00:40:46,641
for whose sacred mission
no sacrifice is too great.

594
00:40:46,744 --> 00:40:50,510
That sounds rather like
something you learnt from a book.

595
00:40:50,614 --> 00:40:54,448
For years, you've had this sort of thing drilled
into you until it's all you know or care about!

596
00:40:54,552 --> 00:40:58,147
<i>You're a fanatic with a
set of stupid, fixed ideasl</i>

597
00:40:59,256 --> 00:41:02,453
If you hadn't made me hate you more than
I thought I could possibly hate anybody...

598
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:04,755
I think I should feel sorry for you.

599
00:41:04,862 --> 00:41:07,660
You have expressed yourself
very clearly, Fraulein Bomasch.

600
00:41:07,765 --> 00:41:12,327
You will be placed in a concentration
camp until your father comes to his senses.

601
00:41:12,436 --> 00:41:15,894
- Must you drag my daughter into this?
- It rests with you, Herr Bomasch.

602
00:41:16,941 --> 00:41:19,239
Hello? What, here?

603
00:41:19,343 --> 00:41:21,470
Very good.

604
00:41:21,579 --> 00:41:23,911
Admiral Hassinger is on his way up.

605
00:41:26,450 --> 00:41:29,977
The Chief of Naval Staff,
Vice Admiral Count Hassinger.

606
00:41:30,087 --> 00:41:32,078
Come in, my dear fellow. Come in.

607
00:41:37,127 --> 00:41:40,995
Strasse, let me present Major
Herzoff of the Corps of Engineers.

608
00:41:41,098 --> 00:41:43,532
I expect you have heard of him.

609
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:46,068
<i>The man behind the
Siegfried line, eh, Herzoff?</i>

610
00:41:46,170 --> 00:41:47,831
<i>[Randall] Only one of the men, sir.</i>

611
00:41:47,938 --> 00:41:51,135
<i>The führer is responsible for the line
as he is responsible for everything.</i>

612
00:41:52,910 --> 00:41:54,878
Well, what progress?

613
00:42:00,518 --> 00:42:04,079
You remember me, Herr Bomasch. I
did not expect to see you again here.

614
00:42:05,122 --> 00:42:08,421
And you, Fraulein Bomasch.
I see you have not forgotten.

615
00:42:09,460 --> 00:42:12,224
It must be... four years.

616
00:42:14,164 --> 00:42:16,064
[Clicks Heels]

617
00:42:17,134 --> 00:42:18,795
[Clicks Heels]

618
00:42:18,903 --> 00:42:22,771
Major Herzoff is preparing a highly
confidential report on armor plating.

619
00:42:22,873 --> 00:42:25,398
He has been on several missions to Prague.

620
00:42:25,509 --> 00:42:28,876
- He met Bomasch there.
- Just one moment, sir.

621
00:42:28,979 --> 00:42:31,971
Marsen, conduct Herr Bomasch and
his daughter into the next room.

622
00:42:33,751 --> 00:42:37,278
- Mr. Bomasch.
- Maybe we shall meet again, later.

623
00:42:44,395 --> 00:42:46,693
I thought it unwise to
speak in front of Bomasch.

624
00:42:46,797 --> 00:42:50,756
- So far, we've made no impression on him.
- I do not agree. He looks 10 years older.

625
00:42:50,868 --> 00:42:52,768
My orders are to obtain quick results.

626
00:42:52,870 --> 00:42:54,770
At the Reich, we are rather
inclined to believe...

627
00:42:54,872 --> 00:42:56,999
that the knuckle-duster is
the best diplomatic weapon.

628
00:42:57,107 --> 00:43:01,806
- Do I understand that you question?
- I question nothing. I am an army officer.

629
00:43:03,247 --> 00:43:06,216
Personally, I do not
follow any of this at all.

630
00:43:06,317 --> 00:43:08,751
Bomasch is not the man to be
bullied into cooperation, sir.

631
00:43:08,852 --> 00:43:10,752
Well, what do you suggest?

632
00:43:10,854 --> 00:43:13,288
I knew Fraulein Bomasch in Prague.

633
00:43:16,994 --> 00:43:20,657
She has a great influence with her father and is
the one person who can make him change his mind.

634
00:43:20,764 --> 00:43:23,392
Oh, Marsen here has tried
that, but she refused to listen.

635
00:43:23,500 --> 00:43:26,492
He is largely responsible for
tracing Bomasch in England...

636
00:43:26,604 --> 00:43:28,902
<i>completely outwitting the
British military intelligence.</i>

637
00:43:29,006 --> 00:43:31,975
So, may I express a soldier's admiration...

638
00:43:32,076 --> 00:43:35,512
<i>for one who can carry out his mission under
the very eyes of the enemy secret service?</i>

639
00:43:35,613 --> 00:43:36,773
Thank you, sir.

640
00:43:36,880 --> 00:43:38,780
But if I may say so, I
hardly think the captain...

641
00:43:38,882 --> 00:43:41,214
is a suitable person to influence the lady.

642
00:43:41,318 --> 00:43:43,445
And who do you think would be more suitable?

643
00:43:43,554 --> 00:43:45,647
Why, uh, myself, for instance.

644
00:43:45,756 --> 00:43:47,383
- You?
- Why not?

645
00:43:47,491 --> 00:43:49,925
Herzoff was very friendly
with her in Prague, you know.

646
00:43:50,027 --> 00:43:52,120
A little more than friendly.

647
00:43:52,229 --> 00:43:54,424
You saw the way she looked
at me when I came in.

648
00:43:54,531 --> 00:43:58,399
Oh, yes, of course. Seems to me
you are a bit of a dog, Herzoff.

649
00:43:58,502 --> 00:44:01,300
A technician, Admiral. One does
not talk about these things...

650
00:44:01,405 --> 00:44:04,431
but I think if I were to spend
a few hours alone with her...

651
00:44:04,541 --> 00:44:07,271
I might induce her to reason with her father.

652
00:44:07,378 --> 00:44:10,973
Oh. What do you think about that, Strasse?

653
00:44:11,081 --> 00:44:13,140
I cannot promise, mind you.

654
00:44:13,250 --> 00:44:15,309
Four years is a long time.

655
00:44:15,419 --> 00:44:17,387
It seems to me it is worth attempting.

656
00:44:17,488 --> 00:44:20,286
- After all, the business is urgent, Strasse.
- It is indeed, sir.

657
00:44:20,391 --> 00:44:24,020
You really believe that you could
influence a girl in a matter of hours?

658
00:44:24,128 --> 00:44:27,154
- Shall we say overnight?
- I see.

659
00:44:27,264 --> 00:44:30,097
Knowing Fraulein Bomasch, sir, I
doubt whether even his qualities...

660
00:44:30,200 --> 00:44:32,100
will make any impression on her.

661
00:44:32,202 --> 00:44:34,727
- You aren't acquainted with my qualities.
- Strasse, we'll let him try it.

662
00:44:34,838 --> 00:44:37,807
No harm done if he doesn't succeed.
Leave all the arrangements to me.

663
00:44:37,908 --> 00:44:41,605
This requires a knowledge of
maneuvers. Come along, Herzoff.

664
00:44:47,017 --> 00:44:49,781
You may be right, my dear.
Bennett may be trying to help us.

665
00:44:49,887 --> 00:44:53,015
But why have they brought us to this
hotel, provided you with clothes?

666
00:44:53,123 --> 00:44:55,023
It doesn't make sense to me.

667
00:44:55,125 --> 00:44:57,685
Well, Bennett's behind it, obviously.
He's organized the whole thing.

668
00:44:57,795 --> 00:44:59,092
How?

669
00:44:59,196 --> 00:45:01,892
Well, how did he manage to get into
the German admiralty as a Nazi officer?

670
00:45:01,999 --> 00:45:04,297
But I don't see how he can
get us away from here, Anna.

671
00:45:04,401 --> 00:45:07,768
Oh, Father, don't worry about it.
Perhaps you'd better go to bed now, eh?

672
00:45:07,871 --> 00:45:09,862
We'll find out what it's
all about in the morning.

673
00:45:09,973 --> 00:45:11,440
- Good night.
- Good night.

674
00:45:11,542 --> 00:45:13,442
Good night, my dear.

675
00:45:26,757 --> 00:45:29,089
<i>[Knocking]</i>

676
00:45:29,193 --> 00:45:31,184
Come in.

677
00:45:32,396 --> 00:45:34,364
- Fraulein Bomasch?
- Yes.

678
00:45:36,366 --> 00:45:38,357
Thank you.

679
00:45:55,819 --> 00:45:58,481
- You are expecting me. Major Herzoff.
- Yes, sir. Good evening.

680
00:45:58,589 --> 00:46:01,558
Your room is Number 18.
Your bags have been taken up.

681
00:46:01,658 --> 00:46:04,456
- My flowers arrive?
- Yes, sir. The lady has them.

682
00:46:04,561 --> 00:46:06,859
<i>- Thank you. Good night.
- Good night, sir.</i>

683
00:46:08,031 --> 00:46:09,999
<i>[Motor Whirring]</i>

684
00:46:15,405 --> 00:46:17,600
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

685
00:46:18,709 --> 00:46:21,303
My darling, you look as charming as ever.

686
00:46:21,411 --> 00:46:24,346
Those same sweet lips, like warm carnations.

687
00:46:25,616 --> 00:46:28,176
<i>Those sweet, mysterious
eyes, darker and softer...</i>

688
00:46:28,285 --> 00:46:30,845
than the bluest dusk of August violets.

689
00:46:30,954 --> 00:46:33,149
As the poet has it, and I hope he was Aryan.

690
00:46:34,291 --> 00:46:36,919
No one under the bed, I trust.

691
00:46:37,027 --> 00:46:39,689
Uh, bring me a bottle of Krug '28.

692
00:46:39,797 --> 00:46:42,595
- That will be excellent.
- What's happening?

693
00:46:42,699 --> 00:46:46,157
Well, you may have gathered that we were
partners in a highly romantic interlude
in Prague four years ago.

694
00:46:46,270 --> 00:46:48,170
- By the way, did you like the flowers?
- Does that matter?

695
00:46:48,272 --> 00:46:50,172
- It cost me 12 coupons.
- Well, go on.

696
00:46:50,274 --> 00:46:52,242
Well, tomorrow morning I'm
going to phone the admiral...

697
00:46:52,342 --> 00:46:54,640
and say that your father is now
prepared to work for Germany.

698
00:46:54,745 --> 00:46:57,043
- What?
- I shall say that I persuaded you
to reason with him.

699
00:46:57,147 --> 00:46:59,138
They're bound to ask me
to take you both along.

700
00:46:59,249 --> 00:47:01,240
The Gestapo man downstairs
will let us pass and then...

701
00:47:01,351 --> 00:47:04,320
- Yes, but how do you know he will?
- They listen in to the phone. They always do.

702
00:47:04,421 --> 00:47:07,390
Then instead of driving to the admiralty,
we shall go to a meadow outside Berlin...

703
00:47:07,491 --> 00:47:09,118
where a plane is waiting.

704
00:47:09,226 --> 00:47:13,185
I see. But why should the admiralty
believe you've persuaded me?

705
00:47:13,297 --> 00:47:17,097
I shall indicate that, uh, once
again you have succumbed to my charms.

706
00:47:18,135 --> 00:47:20,126
Once again?

707
00:47:20,237 --> 00:47:22,933
It happened in Prague, I'm afraid.

708
00:47:23,040 --> 00:47:25,565
And you told them a
fantastic story like that?

709
00:47:25,676 --> 00:47:28,543
Fantastic? Well, it was four years
ago, there was a harvest moon...

710
00:47:28,645 --> 00:47:30,806
and I was younger and more dashing then.

711
00:47:30,914 --> 00:47:34,247
But you really mean all this?
It sounds far too simple.

712
00:47:34,351 --> 00:47:36,285
I have a very simple mind.

713
00:47:36,386 --> 00:47:39,480
But there is one small complication. Uh...

714
00:47:39,590 --> 00:47:41,490
I shall have to spend the night here...

715
00:47:42,860 --> 00:47:45,420
<i>in a purely professional spirit, of course.</i>

716
00:47:45,529 --> 00:47:49,158
<i>- That is necessary?
- Well, sort of fits into the picture.</i>

717
00:47:49,266 --> 00:47:51,234
The place is absolutely
crawling with Gestapo.

718
00:47:52,402 --> 00:47:55,599
- Have you any sporting instinct?
- Why?

719
00:47:55,706 --> 00:47:59,198
<i>Well, I'll, uh, toss you
who sleeps on the couch.</i>

720
00:47:59,309 --> 00:48:01,607
But you're treating all this
as if it were some sort of joke.

721
00:48:01,712 --> 00:48:05,307
- You don't seem to realize
how much depends upon it.
- It's no good being intense about it.

722
00:48:05,415 --> 00:48:08,441
- You don't think I like the idea
of a firing squad, do you?
- What?

723
00:48:08,552 --> 00:48:10,952
England may be at war with Germany tomorrow.

724
00:48:11,054 --> 00:48:15,081
Oh, I see. But don't you think I
ought to tell my father about all this?

725
00:48:15,192 --> 00:48:17,092
- No.
- Why not?

726
00:48:17,194 --> 00:48:20,322
It'd hardly look right for a lovesick
girl to go popping back to her dad.

727
00:48:20,430 --> 00:48:22,330
<i>- [Sighs]
- [Knocking]</i>

728
00:48:24,468 --> 00:48:27,437
That'll be the waiter. If you can pretend
you find me almost unbearably attractive,
so much the better.

729
00:48:27,537 --> 00:48:29,004
- All right. I'll try.
- Thank you.

730
00:48:29,940 --> 00:48:31,635
<i>My little Anna.</i>

731
00:48:32,776 --> 00:48:34,744
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

732
00:48:37,681 --> 00:48:40,149
## [Whistling Tune]

733
00:48:43,687 --> 00:48:45,985
<i>## [Whistling Continues]</i>

734
00:48:48,492 --> 00:48:51,825
- Is it, uh, raining?
- No, miss.

735
00:48:51,929 --> 00:48:54,523
## [Whistling Continues]

736
00:49:03,907 --> 00:49:05,807
Is anything the matter?

737
00:49:05,909 --> 00:49:08,776
That tune you were whistling, sir
- it is an English tune, isn't it?

738
00:49:08,879 --> 00:49:12,042
- How do you know?
- I heard it on the radio from London last night.

739
00:49:12,149 --> 00:49:14,640
Are you not aware that listening to
the foreign broadcasts is forbidden?

740
00:49:14,751 --> 00:49:16,719
- That there is a strict penalty?
- Oh, I'm sorry, sir.

741
00:49:16,820 --> 00:49:19,983
I will not report you on this occasion, but
see that you are more discreet in future.

742
00:49:20,090 --> 00:49:21,557
Get out.

743
00:49:23,093 --> 00:49:25,994
<i>- [Door Closes]
- [Sighs] Very awkward.</i>

744
00:49:26,096 --> 00:49:27,791
Lucky it wasn't "Rule, Britannia!"

745
00:49:27,898 --> 00:49:29,866
I handled it rather neatly, I thought.

746
00:49:29,967 --> 00:49:34,700
If a woman ever loved you like you love yourself,
it would be one of the romances of history.

747
00:49:34,805 --> 00:49:37,797
As I'm unlikely to think of an adequate reply
to that, I think we ought to drink a toast.

748
00:49:37,908 --> 00:49:41,435
England expects that every secret
service man this night shall do his duty.

749
00:49:41,545 --> 00:49:43,979
- [Mild Pop]
- Flat.

750
00:49:46,516 --> 00:49:49,041
<i>[Rhone Rings]</i>

751
00:49:49,152 --> 00:49:51,620
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

752
00:49:52,656 --> 00:49:56,524
- They're ringing your room.
- I'll take it here. It looks better.

753
00:49:56,626 --> 00:49:59,595
<i>- Hello? Is that call for me?
- [Ringing Continues, Stops]</i>

754
00:49:59,696 --> 00:50:01,789
It's German Admiralty.

755
00:50:01,898 --> 00:50:04,662
Yes. Herzoff here. Yes, sir.

756
00:50:04,768 --> 00:50:09,501
I'm sorry to disturb you at this hour,
Herzoff, but we have to alter our plans.

757
00:50:09,606 --> 00:50:12,040
We have just received instructions
from headquarters in Munich...

758
00:50:12,142 --> 00:50:14,736
that Bomasch is to go there
at once by the first train.

759
00:50:14,845 --> 00:50:18,178
But this is ridiculous, sir.
Couldn't you delay it for a few hours?

760
00:50:18,281 --> 00:50:22,183
Impossible. It is on the führer's orders.
The train leaves in an hour's time.

761
00:50:22,285 --> 00:50:25,618
But, sir, what is the use of sending Herr Bomasch
to headquarters in his present frame of mind?

762
00:50:25,722 --> 00:50:28,020
What do you suppose the führer's
frame of mind would be if we didn't?

763
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:31,322
I'm sorry, Herzoff. [Sighs]

764
00:50:32,596 --> 00:50:35,156
- What's happening?
- They're sending you to Munich at once.

765
00:50:35,265 --> 00:50:36,732
- There's only one chance.
- What?

766
00:50:36,833 --> 00:50:40,098
- Leave the hotel, scuttle...
an old German custom.
- But the guards downstairs.

767
00:50:40,203 --> 00:50:42,103
We got into the admiralty.
We'll get out of here.

768
00:50:42,205 --> 00:50:44,503
Get your clothes on. Tell your
father we leave here in five minutes.

769
00:50:45,575 --> 00:50:48,043
<i>[Motor Whirring]</i>

770
00:50:51,882 --> 00:50:54,817
I've been instructed to leave immediately with
Herr Bomasch. I shall not require you. Dismissed.

771
00:50:54,918 --> 00:50:58,354
<i>- [Clerk] Shall I get you a taxi, sir?
- I'll call one myself.</i>

772
00:51:02,559 --> 00:51:04,356
- Good morning, sir.
- [Bennett] Good morning.

773
00:51:04,461 --> 00:51:06,827
I'm here to escort Herr Bomasch
and Fraulein Bomasch to Munich.

774
00:51:06,930 --> 00:51:08,830
The controller phoned me 10 minutes ago.

775
00:51:08,932 --> 00:51:10,900
I was about to drive them
to the admiralty myself.

776
00:51:11,001 --> 00:51:13,060
My orders are to take them
straight to the station.

777
00:51:13,170 --> 00:51:14,797
<i>The train leaves in 50 minutes.</i>

778
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:17,601
Evidently a misunderstanding on my part.

779
00:51:17,707 --> 00:51:21,438
- Very well. We are ready.
- You, sir?

780
00:51:21,545 --> 00:51:23,638
Certainly. Were you not told?

781
00:51:23,747 --> 00:51:25,977
I have the admiral's
authority to travel with them.

782
00:51:28,752 --> 00:51:32,017
He feels it essential that Herr Bomasch should
be persuaded to comply with our wishes...

783
00:51:32,122 --> 00:51:34,090
before he reaches headquarters.

784
00:51:35,125 --> 00:51:38,720
I was progressing extremely well with
Fraulein Bomasch when this happened.

785
00:51:42,432 --> 00:51:45,401
I see. Very good, sir.

786
00:51:46,603 --> 00:51:48,503
[Clicks Heels]

787
00:51:53,210 --> 00:51:57,169
<i>- [Man] Zigaretten! Zigarren!
- [Reople Chattering]</i>

788
00:51:57,280 --> 00:52:00,113
<i>[Trolley Bell Ringing]</i>

789
00:52:00,217 --> 00:52:03,414
<i>- [Man] There's not a copy of this week's Runch?
- Please?</i>

790
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:05,784
<i>Runch. English magazine.</i>

791
00:52:05,889 --> 00:52:08,687
Very humorous. You must have a copy.

792
00:52:08,792 --> 00:52:11,352
No.

793
00:52:11,461 --> 00:52:13,361
<i>She hasn't got a Runch, old man.</i>

794
00:52:13,463 --> 00:52:16,694
<i>- Hasn't she?
- No.</i>

795
00:52:16,800 --> 00:52:20,133
Well. Sold out, I suppose.

796
00:52:20,237 --> 00:52:22,205
[Conductor] You will all leave
here and find places elsewhere.

797
00:52:22,305 --> 00:52:25,206
This compartment is commandeered by the
police. Come along. No delay, please.

798
00:52:25,308 --> 00:52:27,299
<i>They've got La Vie Rarisienne, old boy.</i>

799
00:52:27,410 --> 00:52:30,607
<i>La Vie Rarisienne? All right.
Don't bother about a Runch.</i>

800
00:52:35,886 --> 00:52:38,354
<i>[Candy Vendor Continues In German]</i>

801
00:52:53,904 --> 00:52:56,065
Oh.

802
00:52:56,173 --> 00:52:57,538
Everyone's hopped it.

803
00:52:57,641 --> 00:53:00,667
[Murmurs] Must have got in
the wrong train, I expect.

804
00:53:00,777 --> 00:53:04,008
<i>- [Bell Ringing]
- We can have a side each to ourselves now.</i>

805
00:53:04,114 --> 00:53:07,413
- Put our feet up.
- There.

806
00:53:13,957 --> 00:53:16,084
<i>Bought a copy of Mein Kampf.</i>

807
00:53:16,193 --> 00:53:19,629
Occurred to me it might shed a spot
of light on all this how-do-you-do.

808
00:53:19,729 --> 00:53:22,698
- Ever read it?
- Never had the time.

809
00:53:22,799 --> 00:53:25,768
I understand they give a copy to
all the bridal couples over here.

810
00:53:25,869 --> 00:53:28,201
Oh, I don't think it's
that sort of book, old man.

811
00:53:30,140 --> 00:53:32,540
This is the compart
- Why are you still here?

812
00:53:32,642 --> 00:53:35,577
- What?
- You must find other places at once.

813
00:53:35,679 --> 00:53:37,579
We have first-class tickets, you know.

814
00:53:37,681 --> 00:53:40,377
Outside, please. This compartment has
been commandeered by the authorities.

815
00:53:40,483 --> 00:53:43,452
- That is beside the point.
- Yes. We are British subjects.

816
00:53:43,553 --> 00:53:46,317
Yes. Look here.

817
00:53:49,326 --> 00:53:52,022
"We, Edward Frederick
Lindley, Viscount Halifax...

818
00:53:52,128 --> 00:53:55,393
His Majesty's Principal
Secretary of State" et cetera...

819
00:53:55,498 --> 00:53:58,023
"request all whom it may concern...

820
00:53:58,134 --> 00:54:00,864
<i>"to allow the bearer to pass
without let or hindrance...</i>

821
00:54:00,971 --> 00:54:03,337
<i>and to afford him or her"-</i>

822
00:54:04,808 --> 00:54:06,708
Outside!

823
00:54:14,017 --> 00:54:15,917
- Hmm.
- [Murmurs]

824
00:54:29,232 --> 00:54:33,293
- No good arguing, I suppose.
- Apparently not.

825
00:54:33,403 --> 00:54:36,395
Waste of time, all this
bilge in the passport.

826
00:54:48,618 --> 00:54:51,086
[No Audible Dialogue]

827
00:54:57,794 --> 00:54:59,694
Come, please.

828
00:55:01,931 --> 00:55:04,764
- It's hopeless. We'll never get away now.
- We'll think of something.

829
00:55:04,868 --> 00:55:08,326
- Outside. Come along. Hurry!
- All right. All right.

830
00:55:13,076 --> 00:55:14,976
Hel...

831
00:55:22,819 --> 00:55:24,719
Excuse me.

832
00:55:26,323 --> 00:55:29,417
[Bennett] Now, don't forget that
you're terribly attracted to me.

833
00:55:31,328 --> 00:55:33,796
The two guards' compartment is in there, sir.

834
00:55:33,897 --> 00:55:37,230
All right. Thank you.

835
00:55:43,406 --> 00:55:46,273
- Would you like to face the engine?
- Whatever you like.

836
00:55:55,352 --> 00:55:57,843
Did you notice that German officer
who came into our compartment?

837
00:55:57,954 --> 00:55:59,421
Yes. Why?

838
00:55:59,522 --> 00:56:01,422
Well, I could've sworn
it was old Dicky Randall.

839
00:56:01,524 --> 00:56:03,116
Dicky Randall?

840
00:56:03,226 --> 00:56:05,091
<i>- [Train Whistle Blows]
- Yes. We were at Balliol together.</i>

841
00:56:05,195 --> 00:56:08,528
You must have heard me talking about
him. He used to bowl slow leg breaks.

842
00:56:08,631 --> 00:56:10,531
Played for the Gentlemen once.

843
00:56:10,633 --> 00:56:13,158
Caught and bowled for a duck, I remember.

844
00:56:13,269 --> 00:56:14,964
Oh, yes. Dicky Randall.

845
00:56:15,071 --> 00:56:18,598
Well, if he's a German officer,
how can he be Dicky Randall?

846
00:56:18,708 --> 00:56:21,370
Well, I knew him quite well.
His rooms were next to mine.

847
00:56:21,478 --> 00:56:24,038
Why on earth...

848
00:56:24,147 --> 00:56:27,776
You don't think he's working for the
Nazis like that fellow what's-his-name?

849
00:56:27,884 --> 00:56:31,115
Traitor? Hardly, old man.

850
00:56:31,221 --> 00:56:33,712
He played for the Gentlemen.

851
00:56:33,823 --> 00:56:36,189
Only once.

852
00:56:36,359 --> 00:56:40,056
[Whistle Blowing]

853
00:56:50,907 --> 00:56:53,774
It was last Easter. I was looking
in a shop window in the Graben...

854
00:56:53,877 --> 00:56:56,573
and I saw the reflection of a girl.

855
00:56:56,679 --> 00:56:58,738
For a moment, I thought it was you.

856
00:56:58,848 --> 00:57:02,511
- Were you by yourself?
- Yes. Why?

857
00:57:03,920 --> 00:57:05,888
I just wondered.

858
00:57:12,695 --> 00:57:14,595
It's a blackout.

859
00:57:14,697 --> 00:57:17,996
You know what that means so far west as this.

860
00:57:18,101 --> 00:57:20,433
England and France have declared war.

861
00:57:20,537 --> 00:57:23,802
We have nothing to fear. The
nation is behind the führer.

862
00:57:23,907 --> 00:57:26,239
Yes, but how far behind?

863
00:57:28,778 --> 00:57:30,746
[Anna] We're stopping.

864
00:57:34,184 --> 00:57:36,982
- [Brakes Squealing]
- [Blows Whistle]

865
00:57:37,086 --> 00:57:39,884
Everybody out at once, please!

866
00:57:39,989 --> 00:57:41,889
[Conductor] Everybody out on the platform.

867
00:57:41,991 --> 00:57:45,290
Everybody out of the compartment,
please. Everybody out at once, please.

868
00:57:45,395 --> 00:57:47,295
- [Marsen] Why are we stopping here?
- I don't know yet, sir. Just had the order.

869
00:57:47,397 --> 00:57:50,059
Everybody out, please.
Everybody out. Everybody out.

870
00:57:50,166 --> 00:57:54,466
<i>[Female Conductor Continues, Indistinct]</i>

871
00:57:54,571 --> 00:57:57,369
- How far are we from Munich?
- About an hour's journey.

872
00:57:59,542 --> 00:58:02,238
All passengers off the train, please.

873
00:58:02,345 --> 00:58:05,314
<i>All passengers off the train.</i>

874
00:58:05,415 --> 00:58:08,009
<i>All passengers off the train, please.</i>

875
00:58:08,117 --> 00:58:09,482
- What's happening?
- Everybody-

876
00:58:09,586 --> 00:58:12,146
<i>Heil Hitlerl This train
is required for troops.</i>

877
00:58:12,255 --> 00:58:15,622
There will be only a small amount
of room available for passengers.

878
00:58:15,725 --> 00:58:17,716
<i>- [Marsen] My party must have
the same accommodations.
- Oh, yes.</i>

879
00:58:17,827 --> 00:58:20,193
<i>The train leaves again in 20 minutes.</i>

880
00:58:20,296 --> 00:58:22,196
<i>May I have your carriage number, please, sir?</i>

881
00:58:22,298 --> 00:58:26,200
<i>- Yes. It's, uh, 0735.
- 0735.</i>

882
00:58:29,305 --> 00:58:32,172
Oh, I beg your pardon.
Aren't you old Dicky Randall?

883
00:58:34,177 --> 00:58:36,111
Major Herzoff, Corps of Engineers.

884
00:58:41,885 --> 00:58:44,080
Oh, I'm frightfully sorry.

885
00:58:44,187 --> 00:58:46,587
It was very silly of me,
but it's an amazing likeness.

886
00:58:46,689 --> 00:58:48,589
Yes, you'd better come along, old man.

887
00:58:50,760 --> 00:58:53,320
Extraordinary. English, I presume.

888
00:58:53,429 --> 00:58:55,829
- Apparently.
- They're a very peculiar race.

889
00:58:55,932 --> 00:58:58,901
We have a small waiting room, sir.
Perhaps you would prefer to wait in there.

890
00:58:59,002 --> 00:59:01,163
- Thank you.
- This way, please.

891
00:59:01,271 --> 00:59:03,034
Please. Please, this way.

892
00:59:03,139 --> 00:59:05,664
Everybody off the train now, please!

893
00:59:05,775 --> 00:59:07,902
Everybody off the train!

894
00:59:13,816 --> 00:59:18,446
You know, you... you made me feel
painfully embarrassed, Caldicott.

895
00:59:18,555 --> 00:59:21,285
Well, I can't help it if old
Dicky Randall has a double.

896
00:59:21,391 --> 00:59:25,088
You must realize that we're
traveling in very difficult times.

897
00:59:25,194 --> 00:59:26,821
- [Chuckling]
- What's the matter?

898
00:59:26,930 --> 00:59:31,026
I can't help thinking of your face when he said,
"Major Herzoff, Corps of Engineers".

899
00:59:31,134 --> 00:59:33,261
Well, all I can say, Charters,
is that when it comes to humor...

900
00:59:33,369 --> 00:59:35,428
we live in entirely different worlds.

901
00:59:35,538 --> 00:59:37,028
<i>This waiting room is required.</i>

902
00:59:37,140 --> 00:59:39,734
Every passenger must wait outside. Come on.

903
00:59:39,842 --> 00:59:43,107
<i>Und you too, please. Come
on. So quick like possible.</i>

904
00:59:43,212 --> 00:59:46,238
- This is getting beyond a joke.
- Yes. We can't stand for this.

905
00:59:46,349 --> 00:59:47,816
<i>Come on, please. Out.</i>

906
00:59:47,917 --> 00:59:52,047
Everybody out so quick as possible.
Everybody must wait outside.

907
00:59:52,155 --> 00:59:55,454
<i>All passengers must wait outside. Rlease go.</i>

908
00:59:55,558 --> 00:59:57,924
No good being undignified, old man.

909
00:59:58,027 --> 00:59:59,995
No, quite right.

910
01:00:02,465 --> 01:00:04,626
Come on. Please, please,
please, please. Come on. Come on.

911
01:00:04,734 --> 01:00:08,067
Come on. So. Please. Please. Please.

912
01:00:17,614 --> 01:00:20,947
Oh, Major. May I phone Munich
to notify them of our delay?

913
01:00:21,050 --> 01:00:22,745
Of course.

914
01:00:22,852 --> 01:00:26,310
My absence may provide the opportunity for
Fraulein Bomasch to approach her father.

915
01:00:26,422 --> 01:00:28,117
It might help.

916
01:00:28,224 --> 01:00:31,887
You seem to have made a considerable
impression on the lady, Major.

917
01:00:31,995 --> 01:00:34,759
I apologize for doubting your capabilities.

918
01:00:43,539 --> 01:00:46,940
Stay on guard here. See
that no one enters or leaves.

919
01:00:47,043 --> 01:00:49,341
Understand? No one.

920
01:00:58,454 --> 01:01:01,617
- That man who spoke to you, did you know him?
- Yes, I did. A fellow called Caldicott.

921
01:01:01,724 --> 01:01:04,591
It's probably the first time he's ever left
England before the end of the cricket season.

922
01:01:04,694 --> 01:01:08,494
- Just my luck. He gave me a very nasty moment.
- No one would have guessed it.

923
01:01:08,598 --> 01:01:10,828
I was a member of the Foreign
Office operatic society.

924
01:01:10,933 --> 01:01:13,424
Do you know I once played Pooh-Bah
to the Foreign Secretary's Ko-Ko?

925
01:01:13,536 --> 01:01:15,936
- Have you thought of any way
of getting us out of this?
- I have.

926
01:01:17,040 --> 01:01:19,565
A car will be waiting at Munich
to take us to headquarters.

927
01:01:19,676 --> 01:01:22,975
We'll be quite a crowd, and I shall ask
for a second car so that we can be alone.

928
01:01:23,079 --> 01:01:24,979
- Suppose they don't give it to us.
- They will.

929
01:01:25,081 --> 01:01:28,608
Because by that time, we shall be on the verge
of persuading your father to work for Germany.

930
01:01:28,718 --> 01:01:30,618
You, on the other hand, must
be asking for time to think.

931
01:01:30,720 --> 01:01:32,415
- You get the idea?
- Yes, but...

932
01:01:32,522 --> 01:01:34,513
- Then we only have the chauffeur to deal with.
And after that
- Switzerland.

933
01:01:34,624 --> 01:01:37,991
- Switzerland?
- Well, we can hardly break through
the Siegfried line.

934
01:01:38,094 --> 01:01:40,289
Yes, but Switzerland's
a long way from Munich.

935
01:01:40,396 --> 01:01:42,421
If we can bluff them into giving
us that car, we'll make it.

936
01:01:42,532 --> 01:01:44,500
So from now on, Mr. Bomasch,
you've got to make up your mind...

937
01:01:44,600 --> 01:01:46,966
whether to keep your armor
plating or let it go rusty.

938
01:01:47,070 --> 01:01:48,970
- Is that quite clear?
- I think so.

939
01:01:49,072 --> 01:01:53,065
And you're still so crazy about me
that you would sell the armor plating
for a very small lock of my hair.

940
01:01:53,176 --> 01:01:54,643
All right.

941
01:01:57,113 --> 01:01:59,946
You can't sit here!

942
01:02:00,049 --> 01:02:01,949
- Why not?
- This truck is required.

943
01:02:02,051 --> 01:02:04,144
Come on. Off, off, off, off, off, off.

944
01:02:04,253 --> 01:02:06,346
I suppose these bags aren't required too?

945
01:02:06,456 --> 01:02:09,220
Off, off, off, off, off, off, off.

946
01:02:09,325 --> 01:02:13,261
Pushed about from pillar to post by this
railway ever since we got on the train.

947
01:02:13,362 --> 01:02:16,126
- Everything we sit on seems to be required.
- It's monstrous.

948
01:02:16,232 --> 01:02:18,063
- We shall write to the company about this.
- Hmm!

949
01:02:18,167 --> 01:02:19,794
You're not at war with England yet, you know.

950
01:02:19,902 --> 01:02:22,496
But you are mistaken.

951
01:02:22,605 --> 01:02:24,698
<i>France declared war this afternoon.</i>

952
01:02:24,807 --> 01:02:27,674
<i>Und England declared war this morning. So!</i>

953
01:02:27,777 --> 01:02:30,405
<i>Achtungl</i>

954
01:02:40,790 --> 01:02:42,690
War.

955
01:02:44,594 --> 01:02:47,461
<i>[Rapers Flop]</i>

956
01:02:47,563 --> 01:02:49,588
Yes.

957
01:02:50,700 --> 01:02:53,362
- Good heavens.
- What's the matter?

958
01:02:53,469 --> 01:02:55,937
My golf clubs.

959
01:02:56,038 --> 01:02:58,268
Where are they?

960
01:02:58,374 --> 01:03:00,433
I lent them to Max in Berlin.

961
01:03:00,543 --> 01:03:03,341
Like a fool, I said he needn't
bring them back till next Wednesday.

962
01:03:05,281 --> 01:03:08,546
[Exhales] Probably seen the last of them.

963
01:03:08,651 --> 01:03:12,553
Yes. I expect they'll require
them for something or other.

964
01:03:12,655 --> 01:03:15,715
I read in the paper that
they're pulling up park railings.

965
01:03:15,825 --> 01:03:17,588
I don't see the connection, old man.

966
01:03:17,693 --> 01:03:21,390
Well, your clubs are steel, aren't they?

967
01:03:24,167 --> 01:03:26,260
- Yes.
- So.

968
01:03:26,369 --> 01:03:28,769
There you are then.

969
01:03:28,871 --> 01:03:30,566
Whip shafts too.

970
01:03:30,673 --> 01:03:33,107
Especially made for me.

971
01:03:33,209 --> 01:03:35,074
Why not get in touch with Max?

972
01:03:35,178 --> 01:03:37,840
- How?
- On the telephone.

973
01:03:37,947 --> 01:03:40,142
Ask him to send them to London immediately.

974
01:03:40,249 --> 01:03:42,217
It's a desperate chance,
but it's worth taking.

975
01:03:42,318 --> 01:03:44,286
I shall never be able to replace them.

976
01:03:52,562 --> 01:03:54,928
- Oh, uh, telephone?
- Hmm?

977
01:03:55,031 --> 01:03:56,931
Stationmaster's office.

978
01:04:05,608 --> 01:04:07,838
Captain Strasse? Marsen here.

979
01:04:07,944 --> 01:04:10,572
- I'm speaking from Kurtbaden.
- Oh, I beg your pardon.

980
01:04:14,650 --> 01:04:16,709
It concerns Major Herzoff, sir.

981
01:04:16,819 --> 01:04:18,719
I think a full inquiry
should be made at once...

982
01:04:18,821 --> 01:04:20,982
in view of something which
happened a few minutes ago.

983
01:04:21,090 --> 01:04:24,753
A few minutes ago? You mean he's with you?

984
01:04:24,861 --> 01:04:26,954
Admiral Hassinger gave him the authority.

985
01:04:27,063 --> 01:04:29,861
Hassinger did? He never told me.

986
01:04:29,966 --> 01:04:31,593
That's very suspicious.

987
01:04:31,701 --> 01:04:34,761
Yes, but the admiral himself introduced him.

988
01:04:34,871 --> 01:04:36,395
I'll ask him. I'll phone you back.

989
01:04:36,505 --> 01:04:38,473
Uh, what is your number there?

990
01:04:40,209 --> 01:04:42,177
Yes, yes, yes. In a few minutes.

991
01:04:45,948 --> 01:04:47,848
Admiral Hassinger, please.

992
01:04:47,950 --> 01:04:50,783
<i>[Train Rassing]</i>

993
01:05:04,233 --> 01:05:07,725
Hello? I want a
long-distance call to Berlin.

994
01:05:07,837 --> 01:05:09,737
Oliver
2-4-double 6.

995
01:05:09,839 --> 01:05:13,275
What? Yes. Yes, of course it's important.

996
01:05:17,179 --> 01:05:19,306
- It's all in German.
- Hmm.

997
01:05:19,415 --> 01:05:21,110
What?

998
01:05:21,217 --> 01:05:23,617
Well, how long then? Oh, all right.

999
01:05:25,054 --> 01:05:28,854
Blasted junction's engaged by the
military. They'll call me back.

1000
01:05:28,958 --> 01:05:31,825
These people seem to have
no idea of business as usual.

1001
01:05:41,737 --> 01:05:45,434
If I were asked to give a snap
judgment, I should say that was an "S."

1002
01:05:45,541 --> 01:05:47,566
- More like an "F."
- I do not know, sir.

1003
01:05:47,677 --> 01:05:50,840
I used to know someone
who made his S's like that.

1004
01:05:50,947 --> 01:05:53,848
- Someone in the War Office?
- Well, no.

1005
01:05:53,950 --> 01:05:56,009
<i>Ach. We can't afford to waste time.</i>

1006
01:05:56,118 --> 01:05:58,086
You didn't give him permission to
travel with the prisoners, did you, sir?

1007
01:05:58,187 --> 01:06:00,087
No, no. But he may have assumed it.

1008
01:06:00,189 --> 01:06:02,487
If you remember, we more or
less gave him carte blanche.

1009
01:06:02,591 --> 01:06:04,491
The only thing is to check
up with the War Office, sir.

1010
01:06:04,593 --> 01:06:06,060
- I suppose so.
- War Office.

1011
01:06:06,162 --> 01:06:08,995
If he's right, this will be
very serious for you, Kampfeldt.

1012
01:06:09,098 --> 01:06:10,565
Very serious indeed.

1013
01:06:10,666 --> 01:06:13,328
The letter was addressed to you.
There's no denying that, Kampfeldt.

1014
01:06:13,436 --> 01:06:16,997
Quite right. I'm afraid I
shall have to sack my secretary.

1015
01:06:17,106 --> 01:06:18,403
Hello?

1016
01:06:22,144 --> 01:06:25,113
<i>[Soldier Speaking German]</i>

1017
01:06:25,214 --> 01:06:28,775
<i>- [Rhone Rings]
- That'll be our call.</i>

1018
01:06:28,884 --> 01:06:30,784
<i>- [Soldier Continues]
- [Ringing Continues]</i>

1019
01:06:30,886 --> 01:06:32,581
Aufschliessen!

1020
01:06:33,956 --> 01:06:36,891
Hmm! What infernal impudence.

1021
01:06:36,993 --> 01:06:39,223
I'll bet it's my call.

1022
01:06:39,328 --> 01:06:43,594
Marsen speaking. Yes, sir.

1023
01:06:43,699 --> 01:06:46,327
Listen, Marsen. You were right.
We have been completely fooled.

1024
01:06:46,435 --> 01:06:48,335
Herzoff is not known at the War Office.

1025
01:06:48,437 --> 01:06:50,496
There is no officer of
that name on the army list.

1026
01:06:50,606 --> 01:06:52,972
Then, uh...

1027
01:06:53,075 --> 01:06:56,238
Yes, sir. Obviously. An enemy agent.

1028
01:06:59,382 --> 01:07:01,748
I say, Charters, there's
another phone in there.

1029
01:07:01,851 --> 01:07:04,149
What? Oh. Lucky.

1030
01:07:05,621 --> 01:07:09,182
<i>- [Soldier Shouts In German]
- Hello? Hello? Hello!</i>

1031
01:07:10,359 --> 01:07:14,455
- Gone dead.
- [Cradle Clattering]

1032
01:07:14,563 --> 01:07:17,293
- Hello!
- Why not try the thingamy? Yeah.

1033
01:07:17,400 --> 01:07:19,300
- You know, the... gadget.
- Oh.

1034
01:07:21,103 --> 01:07:23,003
Hello...

1035
01:07:26,108 --> 01:07:28,736
It's the extension. That chap out there.

1036
01:07:29,779 --> 01:07:32,009
Well, perhaps he'll be
off the line in a minute.

1037
01:07:32,114 --> 01:07:34,708
- Shh!
- What's up?

1038
01:07:34,817 --> 01:07:37,377
They're talking
about what's-his-name.

1039
01:07:37,486 --> 01:07:40,046
You know, Herzoff.

1040
01:07:40,156 --> 01:07:42,886
No. He doesn't suspect.

1041
01:07:44,660 --> 01:07:47,220
Yes, sir. I see.

1042
01:07:47,329 --> 01:07:50,560
<i>[Female Conductor] All
passengers aboard, pleasel</i>

1043
01:07:50,666 --> 01:07:53,157
No time to stand here now,
sir. The train is leaving.

1044
01:07:53,269 --> 01:07:56,136
What? Listen, we can't afford to take risks.

1045
01:07:56,238 --> 01:07:58,206
Carry on with Herzoff to Munich.

1046
01:07:58,307 --> 01:08:00,867
Let him think he's getting
away with it. Understand?

1047
01:08:00,976 --> 01:08:03,171
I'll get on to army headquarters there.

1048
01:08:03,279 --> 01:08:04,746
Very good, sir.

1049
01:08:04,847 --> 01:08:07,714
<i>All passengers aboard, pleasel</i>

1050
01:08:09,285 --> 01:08:12,152
<i>- Everybody on the trainl
- What is it?</i>

1051
01:08:12,254 --> 01:08:16,213
Well, as far as I can make
out, Herzoff isn't Herzoff.

1052
01:08:16,325 --> 01:08:17,622
- What?
- No.

1053
01:08:17,726 --> 01:08:21,287
They're sending an escort to arrest him
- when we get to Munich.

1054
01:08:21,397 --> 01:08:24,025
- Herzoff?
- Yes.

1055
01:08:24,133 --> 01:08:26,693
- Well
- Then...

1056
01:08:26,802 --> 01:08:30,704
- Listen, if... if Herzoff isn't Herzoff...
- What?

1057
01:08:30,806 --> 01:08:34,071
- Well, he must be Dicky Randall.
- Yes.

1058
01:08:34,343 --> 01:08:38,609
Everybody on the train! All
passengers aboard, please!

1059
01:08:42,751 --> 01:08:46,915
All passengers on the last two coaches only!

1060
01:08:47,022 --> 01:08:49,081
All passengers aboard!

1061
01:08:49,191 --> 01:08:51,819
<i>- All passengers aboard.
- After you, Major.</i>

1062
01:08:51,927 --> 01:08:55,158
<i>All passengers on the last two coaches only.</i>

1063
01:08:55,264 --> 01:08:58,791
<i>All passengers on the last two coaches.</i>

1064
01:08:58,901 --> 01:09:01,096
<i>All passengers aboard.</i>

1065
01:09:01,203 --> 01:09:05,606
<i>All passengers on the last two coaches only.</i>

1066
01:09:05,708 --> 01:09:09,144
<i>All passengers on the last two coaches.</i>

1067
01:09:09,245 --> 01:09:11,145
<i>All passengers aboard.</i>

1068
01:09:11,247 --> 01:09:14,739
Keep within call. I shall need
you at Munich, perhaps before.

1069
01:09:16,986 --> 01:09:18,453
[Blows Whistle]

1070
01:09:18,554 --> 01:09:21,114
<i>- One thing emerges very clearly from all this.
- [Train Whistle Blows]</i>

1071
01:09:22,791 --> 01:09:25,624
- Caldicott!
- The train! There it goes!

1072
01:09:25,728 --> 01:09:27,992
Oh, my, my! That's a mess!

1073
01:09:28,097 --> 01:09:30,327
<i>[Train Departing]</i>

1074
01:09:40,676 --> 01:09:44,737
- [Panting]
- [Caldicott] That was a near thing.

1075
01:09:44,847 --> 01:09:47,782
[Charters] I thought we were going to be
in this infernal country for the duration.

1076
01:09:47,883 --> 01:09:49,783
Oh, my Lord.

1077
01:10:23,085 --> 01:10:24,985
Don't anticipate, old man.

1078
01:10:34,863 --> 01:10:38,697
What were you saying just now about
something emerging very clearly?

1079
01:10:38,801 --> 01:10:40,928
- I said?
- Mmm.

1080
01:10:41,036 --> 01:10:43,732
- When?
- On the platform.

1081
01:10:43,839 --> 01:10:46,569
- About something emerging?
- Mmm.

1082
01:10:46,675 --> 01:10:49,439
What was it?

1083
01:10:49,545 --> 01:10:51,445
- What was what?
- What emerged.

1084
01:10:51,547 --> 01:10:54,675
- You never said.
- Oh.

1085
01:10:54,783 --> 01:10:57,513
We do not wish to persuade you to become
a National Socialist, Herr Bomasch.

1086
01:10:57,620 --> 01:10:59,520
I explained that to your
daughter. Have I not?

1087
01:10:59,622 --> 01:11:01,453
And you may work wherever you choose, Father.

1088
01:11:01,557 --> 01:11:02,854
- Isn't that so?
- Quite.

1089
01:11:02,958 --> 01:11:05,392
- After all, we should have our freedom.
- I know, my dear.

1090
01:11:05,494 --> 01:11:08,258
But freedom is strangely
interpreted in this country.

1091
01:11:08,364 --> 01:11:10,332
I do not agree with you, Herr Bomasch.

1092
01:11:10,432 --> 01:11:13,492
Freedom in Germany is a great
advance on freedom elsewhere.

1093
01:11:13,602 --> 01:11:16,571
It's properly organized
and controlled by the state.

1094
01:11:16,672 --> 01:11:19,072
I'd much rather we kept politics out of it.

1095
01:11:19,174 --> 01:11:21,301
Herr Bomasch unfortunately
refuses to understand...

1096
01:11:21,410 --> 01:11:23,401
the sacred importance of
the Nazi world mission.

1097
01:11:23,512 --> 01:11:26,948
- His stay in England perhaps.
- No doubt. A corrupt influence.

1098
01:11:27,049 --> 01:11:29,176
A corrupt country.

1099
01:11:30,352 --> 01:11:33,788
Controlled by international
Freemasons and theJew Churchill.

1100
01:11:36,225 --> 01:11:37,749
[Clicks]

1101
01:11:37,860 --> 01:11:40,886
But since you wish it, Herr
Bomasch, we will drop politics...

1102
01:11:40,996 --> 01:11:43,055
and discuss it from a more personal basis.

1103
01:11:43,165 --> 01:11:45,963
I'm certain, Charters, that
what you were about to say...

1104
01:11:46,068 --> 01:11:49,435
was that we've stumbled on
something pretty serious.

1105
01:11:49,538 --> 01:11:51,870
There's no doubt which
side Randall's playing for.

1106
01:11:51,974 --> 01:11:54,408
- Ours?
- Yes.

1107
01:11:54,510 --> 01:11:58,344
Yes. That's what was emerging so clearly.

1108
01:11:58,447 --> 01:12:00,677
It's up to us to find
some way of warning him.

1109
01:12:00,783 --> 01:12:03,445
Yes. Come on. Let's find him.

1110
01:12:11,093 --> 01:12:12,993
- I say, Caldicott.
- Yes?

1111
01:12:13,095 --> 01:12:15,655
- Do you think we're wise rushing into this?
- How do you mean?

1112
01:12:15,764 --> 01:12:18,858
Well, I mean we've no proof that
Randall's working for England.

1113
01:12:18,967 --> 01:12:20,958
- Well, everything points to it.
- Yes, but is that enough?

1114
01:12:21,070 --> 01:12:22,970
We're enemy aliens...

1115
01:12:23,072 --> 01:12:25,836
and these Nazis are pretty
free with their firing party.

1116
01:12:25,941 --> 01:12:28,671
Hmm. Well, ought we to
let that stand in our way?

1117
01:12:28,777 --> 01:12:31,541
Well, certainly not.

1118
01:12:31,647 --> 01:12:34,138
I mean if
- if we were certain.

1119
01:12:35,617 --> 01:12:40,179
As it is, we've just got to bear it in mind.

1120
01:12:40,289 --> 01:12:42,689
I don't see what else he can be doing.

1121
01:12:42,791 --> 01:12:45,851
For all we know, he may
be an international crook.

1122
01:12:45,961 --> 01:12:48,555
Crooks don't generally
play for the Gentlemen.

1123
01:12:49,732 --> 01:12:51,700
Raffles did.

1124
01:12:53,168 --> 01:12:55,295
That's fiction.

1125
01:12:55,404 --> 01:12:57,770
Still, you may be right, Charters.

1126
01:13:00,943 --> 01:13:04,606
Of course, if we were certain,
we'd do our duty and take the risk.

1127
01:13:04,713 --> 01:13:06,180
Yes, of course.

1128
01:13:06,281 --> 01:13:09,273
<i>As it is, I can get on with Mein Kampf.</i>

1129
01:13:09,385 --> 01:13:12,149
Haven't got out of Hitler's boyhood yet.

1130
01:13:12,254 --> 01:13:14,518
And, Herr Bomasch, what
is even more important...

1131
01:13:14,623 --> 01:13:17,558
your daughter will be able to live
with you or wherever she pleases.

1132
01:13:17,659 --> 01:13:20,321
- You must give me time to think.
- Certainly.

1133
01:13:22,498 --> 01:13:25,126
We should be in Munich in... 40 minutes.

1134
01:13:25,234 --> 01:13:29,068
Indeed. For the first time, I will
be sorry when the journey's over.

1135
01:13:30,839 --> 01:13:33,307
Yes. I
- I can believe that.

1136
01:13:34,343 --> 01:13:37,244
- I think we should order something to eat.
- An excellent idea.

1137
01:13:37,346 --> 01:13:41,874
Just in case we do not find headquarters
in a very... hospitable frame of mind.

1138
01:13:44,453 --> 01:13:46,648
- Please.
- Oh, sorry.

1139
01:13:48,424 --> 01:13:51,222
You don't choose to stand up
when a German officer passes?

1140
01:13:51,326 --> 01:13:53,226
You see, we're English.

1141
01:13:54,430 --> 01:13:56,398
Your passports.

1142
01:13:59,301 --> 01:14:02,737
Oh, beg your pardon. You're quite right.

1143
01:14:02,838 --> 01:14:04,965
The English should not stand up.

1144
01:14:05,073 --> 01:14:08,065
They should go down on
their fat bellies and crawl.

1145
01:14:08,177 --> 01:14:10,077
- Now look here!
- So, you are standing up.

1146
01:14:10,179 --> 01:14:13,376
Very well. We shall generously
permit you to run back to England...

1147
01:14:13,482 --> 01:14:16,645
no doubt to find yourselves safe jobs.

1148
01:14:16,752 --> 01:14:19,653
Meanwhile, you may sit down.

1149
01:14:22,124 --> 01:14:25,719
- "Fat bellies".
- "Safe jobs".

1150
01:14:25,828 --> 01:14:27,887
As if they weren't all taken by now anyway.

1151
01:14:27,996 --> 01:14:30,794
Caldicott, this is absolutely
and finally the last straw.

1152
01:14:30,899 --> 01:14:33,925
- Yes, Charters.
- We'll warn Dicky Randall at once,
come what may.

1153
01:14:34,036 --> 01:14:35,936
I'm with you, old man.

1154
01:14:36,038 --> 01:14:38,700
It's things like that
that bring it home to you.

1155
01:14:38,807 --> 01:14:41,571
Sandwiches, biscuits. Yes, sir.

1156
01:14:41,677 --> 01:14:43,577
Will you take tea substitute
or coffee substitute?

1157
01:14:43,679 --> 01:14:45,146
Tea for me, please.

1158
01:14:45,247 --> 01:14:46,714
- Tea.
- Fine.

1159
01:14:51,386 --> 01:14:53,877
He's in there. That
Gestapo fellow's there too.

1160
01:14:53,989 --> 01:14:55,889
Yes. A couple of storm troopers in there.

1161
01:14:55,991 --> 01:14:58,824
How the devil are we going to pass him
the word without that fellow spotting it?

1162
01:14:58,927 --> 01:15:01,088
- We've got to do it somehow.
- Yes.

1163
01:15:01,196 --> 01:15:05,189
Of course, he... he might come out for a minute.
I mean, most people do.

1164
01:15:06,235 --> 01:15:09,602
We must act, Charters. It's no good
hanging about on the off chance.

1165
01:15:09,705 --> 01:15:11,673
Excuse, please.

1166
01:15:16,512 --> 01:15:19,845
- Wait a minute. That steward.
- What about him?

1167
01:15:19,948 --> 01:15:22,416
Well, he's bound to come back
sometime to bring their order.

1168
01:15:22,518 --> 01:15:24,418
ByJove, yes.

1169
01:15:39,635 --> 01:15:41,535
Here he comes.

1170
01:15:41,637 --> 01:15:45,004
- ## [Whistling]
- Excuse, please.

1171
01:15:45,107 --> 01:15:47,940
- Oh, what... what time do we get to Munich?
- In about 30 minutes, sir.

1172
01:15:48,043 --> 01:15:50,511
<i>Thank you.</i>

1173
01:15:53,916 --> 01:15:56,908
- All right?
- Yes. I put it underneath a doughnut.

1174
01:15:57,019 --> 01:16:00,113
Good. What? But how do
you know they're for him?

1175
01:16:00,222 --> 01:16:02,850
Well, I suddenly remembered that
Dicky Randall always had doughnuts...

1176
01:16:02,958 --> 01:16:04,858
sent up to his room for afternoon tea.

1177
01:16:04,960 --> 01:16:07,394
[Chuckles] That's very
clever of you, old man.

1178
01:16:07,496 --> 01:16:09,896
- Better get along there, hey?
- Mmm, right.

1179
01:16:10,666 --> 01:16:12,691
- Oh, my Lord.
- Why, what's up?

1180
01:16:12,801 --> 01:16:15,099
Why, I'm
- I'm wondering if it was doughnuts.

1181
01:16:15,203 --> 01:16:17,603
- What?
- I-I believe it was rock cakes.

1182
01:16:19,541 --> 01:16:21,441
[Exhales]

1183
01:16:25,047 --> 01:16:27,709
Have you made all arrangements
for transport at Munich, Marsen?

1184
01:16:27,816 --> 01:16:29,306
Every arrangement, sir.

1185
01:16:29,418 --> 01:16:33,514
- Will there be more than one car?
- Almost certainly two.

1186
01:16:33,622 --> 01:16:35,988
Then let's see, that will
make seven. Rather a crowd.

1187
01:16:36,091 --> 01:16:39,151
I think in order to finish my talk with Herr
Bomasch, you had better take the second car.

1188
01:16:39,261 --> 01:16:41,593
Very good, sir.

1189
01:16:46,068 --> 01:16:49,834
<i>I believe Herr Bomasch is really beginning
to see that I am doing my best to help him.</i>

1190
01:16:49,938 --> 01:16:51,633
I'm sure he knows that.

1191
01:16:51,740 --> 01:16:53,901
Yes, yes, Major. Your attitude
has been most reasonable.

1192
01:16:54,009 --> 01:16:58,036
You must remember it's only a few hours since
Father was taken out of England by force.

1193
01:16:58,146 --> 01:17:00,580
Captain Marsen was only obeying orders.

1194
01:17:00,682 --> 01:17:02,809
Members of the Gestapo are
frequently asked to perform duties...

1195
01:17:02,918 --> 01:17:04,818
which others find too objectionable.

1196
01:17:04,920 --> 01:17:07,286
Some are objectionable.

1197
01:17:07,389 --> 01:17:09,721
Others I find extremely satisfying.

1198
01:17:09,825 --> 01:17:12,225
<i>[Bennett] I often envy
you your opportunities.</i>

1199
01:17:19,635 --> 01:17:24,732
<i>[Train Whistle Blowing]</i>

1200
01:17:26,174 --> 01:17:29,541
What is that, the bill? I will pay.

1201
01:17:29,645 --> 01:17:31,545
No, please. I am escorting the party.

1202
01:17:31,647 --> 01:17:33,979
My dear Marsen, it's my privilege.

1203
01:17:34,082 --> 01:17:36,414
In fact, it is an order.

1204
01:17:44,393 --> 01:17:48,295
Terrible. The way prices
have gone up already.

1205
01:17:57,806 --> 01:18:00,070
Excuse me.

1206
01:18:19,027 --> 01:18:20,494
[Clicks Heels]

1207
01:18:39,614 --> 01:18:41,582
- Yes, I-I'm Randall.
- How are you, old man?

1208
01:18:41,683 --> 01:18:43,150
- You remember me?
- Yes.

1209
01:18:43,251 --> 01:18:45,947
- This is Charters, an old friend of mine.
- How do you do? Well, what is it?

1210
01:18:46,054 --> 01:18:48,488
- We don't know what you're up to, of course.
- Never mind about that.

1211
01:18:48,590 --> 01:18:51,354
But whatever it is, you appear to be on
the spot. Tell him about it, Charters.

1212
01:18:51,460 --> 01:18:53,792
Well, I was phoning
Berlin about my golf clubs.

1213
01:18:53,895 --> 01:18:56,125
By the way, I'm resigned to the fact I
shall never see them again, Caldicott.

1214
01:18:56,231 --> 01:18:58,131
- Yes, well, get on with it.
- I was just coming to that.

1215
01:18:58,233 --> 01:19:01,691
I was telephoning and got on the other
chap's line... you know, that Gestapo fellow.

1216
01:19:01,803 --> 01:19:04,203
I overheard him saying they
were sending a military escort...

1217
01:19:04,306 --> 01:19:06,069
to arrest you when you get to Munich.

1218
01:19:06,174 --> 01:19:08,734
You see, you're rumbled. They
know that you're not Herzoff.

1219
01:19:11,613 --> 01:19:14,173
Now listen. I can't tell you
everything. There isn't time.

1220
01:19:14,282 --> 01:19:17,410
But I've got to get that old man and the
girl out of this country at all costs.

1221
01:19:17,519 --> 01:19:19,953
Oh, a
- an official job.

1222
01:19:20,055 --> 01:19:22,216
- Are you two fellows game to help me?
- What, against Germany?

1223
01:19:22,324 --> 01:19:24,792
I'll say we are after all they've
done to us. What do you say, Caldicott?

1224
01:19:24,893 --> 01:19:28,385
- Absolutely, old man. Backs to the wall.
- I hope not.

1225
01:19:28,497 --> 01:19:30,897
I say, could you give me a
little more room to think?

1226
01:19:46,114 --> 01:19:47,581
[Clicks Heels]

1227
01:19:54,556 --> 01:19:57,389
- Is there any tea left?
- Yes, I think so, Ulrich.

1228
01:19:57,492 --> 01:20:00,586
There's no time for tea. We
reach Munich in a few minutes.

1229
01:20:00,695 --> 01:20:03,027
Oh, time for just one cup. Cake, darling?

1230
01:20:03,131 --> 01:20:04,598
No, thank you.

1231
01:20:04,699 --> 01:20:08,135
I am afraid I must ask you
to drop this little comedy.

1232
01:20:08,236 --> 01:20:11,967
It is very entertaining, but I have
certain formalities to attend to.

1233
01:20:12,073 --> 01:20:13,973
Comedy? What do you mean?

1234
01:20:14,075 --> 01:20:15,940
Oh, thank you.

1235
01:20:16,044 --> 01:20:20,174
You're merely pretending to
be infatuated with this man.

1236
01:20:20,282 --> 01:20:22,546
There's no such person as Major Herzoff.

1237
01:20:22,651 --> 01:20:26,781
<i>He's a British agent trying to get
you and your father out of Germany.</i>

1238
01:20:26,888 --> 01:20:29,322
You must be crazy. Ulrich.

1239
01:20:29,424 --> 01:20:31,756
I don't propose to waste the
time of the Gestapo denying it.

1240
01:20:31,860 --> 01:20:33,384
Thank you.

1241
01:20:33,495 --> 01:20:36,089
You... You're going to give yourself up?

1242
01:20:36,198 --> 01:20:38,257
Well, they have lots of proof, Mr. Bomasch.

1243
01:20:38,366 --> 01:20:41,233
An escort will be waiting at
Munich to take you in charge.

1244
01:20:43,905 --> 01:20:45,805
You can't do this.

1245
01:20:45,907 --> 01:20:48,068
- He's an enemy agent.
- Weren't you?

1246
01:20:48,176 --> 01:20:50,144
Didn't you do exactly the same as he's doing?

1247
01:20:50,245 --> 01:20:54,113
With a slight but important
difference. I wasn't caught.

1248
01:20:58,286 --> 01:21:02,188
- Are you just going to sit there and do nothing?
- Now, please don't make a scene.

1249
01:21:02,290 --> 01:21:04,918
<i>- Don't you realize what this means?
- Yes, I do.</i>

1250
01:21:05,026 --> 01:21:09,429
But he has a gun, and I haven't. And
he's got a couple of reserves next door.

1251
01:21:09,531 --> 01:21:11,499
Who do you take me for
- Bulldog Drummond?

1252
01:21:11,600 --> 01:21:13,295
[Sighs]

1253
01:21:13,401 --> 01:21:16,598
Can't you be serious even now?
I told you this would happen.

1254
01:21:16,705 --> 01:21:19,936
I told you your scheme was absolutely
childish, but you wouldn't listen to me.

1255
01:21:20,041 --> 01:21:22,339
Why didn't you stay in England
instead of coming over here...

1256
01:21:22,444 --> 01:21:25,641
and deliberately throwing
your life away, you fool?

1257
01:21:33,788 --> 01:21:36,313
I have no time to listen
to this ridiculous display.

1258
01:21:39,895 --> 01:21:41,362
Steiner! Dreimund!

1259
01:21:46,534 --> 01:21:49,002
<i>[Train Whistle Blowing]</i>

1260
01:21:53,308 --> 01:21:55,503
<i>[Soldier Shouting Orders In German]</i>

1261
01:21:57,045 --> 01:21:59,172
<i>[Soldier #2 Shouting Orders]</i>

1262
01:21:59,281 --> 01:22:02,341
<i>[Bell Ringing]</i>

1263
01:22:02,450 --> 01:22:04,475
If there is more than
one major on the train...

1264
01:22:04,586 --> 01:22:06,918
how are we to know which one to arrest?

1265
01:22:07,022 --> 01:22:08,922
Our man's got a Gestapo officer watching him.

1266
01:22:09,024 --> 01:22:10,491
Hmm. Who has not these days?

1267
01:22:10,592 --> 01:22:13,220
<i>- [Train Whistle Blowing]
- The train.</i>

1268
01:22:29,744 --> 01:22:32,212
[Brakes Squealing]

1269
01:23:00,108 --> 01:23:02,235
<i>- Heil Hitler.
- Heil Hitlerl</i>

1270
01:23:02,344 --> 01:23:06,713
Marsen. I'm on instruction from Fifth
Army Headquarters to arrest Major Herzoff.

1271
01:23:06,815 --> 01:23:08,783
I fear you will need a stretcher.

1272
01:23:08,883 --> 01:23:12,546
The prisoner tried to escape, and I had to, uh
- to deal with him.

1273
01:23:12,654 --> 01:23:14,918
You will find him in the
last compartment, Coach 66.

1274
01:23:16,091 --> 01:23:18,321
Uh, what... what transport have you?

1275
01:23:18,426 --> 01:23:20,417
- Two cars.
- Excellent.

1276
01:23:20,528 --> 01:23:23,827
Now, this is Herr Axel Bomasch
from Harska and his daughter.

1277
01:23:23,932 --> 01:23:26,059
They are in protective custody,
and I have instructions...

1278
01:23:26,167 --> 01:23:28,499
to take them to General
von Komwitz without delay.

1279
01:23:28,603 --> 01:23:30,969
<i>With your permission, I
will use one of the cars.</i>

1280
01:23:31,072 --> 01:23:33,734
<i>- [Officer] Certainly.
- I'll leave you to take charge of the prisoner.</i>

1281
01:23:33,842 --> 01:23:35,742
Will you show me my car?

1282
01:23:35,844 --> 01:23:37,368
- Brunner.
- [Clicks Heels]

1283
01:23:37,479 --> 01:23:39,913
Take this S.S. officer to the car.

1284
01:23:40,015 --> 01:23:42,483
- Coach 66 you said?
- The last compartment.

1285
01:23:43,518 --> 01:23:45,486
Full length on the seat.

1286
01:23:46,654 --> 01:23:50,681
Sergeant, get a stretcher from
the stationmaster and follow me.

1287
01:23:58,400 --> 01:24:01,699
Olson, you will take the S.S.
officer and his party in your car.

1288
01:24:04,105 --> 01:24:06,733
One moment. Is your chauffeur to be trusted?

1289
01:24:06,841 --> 01:24:08,934
I think so. He is a very
old member of the party.

1290
01:24:09,044 --> 01:24:11,638
Anti-Russian perhaps. I think
I'd rather take one of my own men.

1291
01:24:11,746 --> 01:24:14,237
- I'm traveling to a place
of the greatest secrecy.
- Very good.

1292
01:24:14,349 --> 01:24:16,681
- You will not be needed, Olson.
- Very good, sir.

1293
01:24:18,086 --> 01:24:20,179
Rumplemeyer, you will drive.

1294
01:24:21,990 --> 01:24:23,787
- Heil Hitler.
- Heil Hitler.

1295
01:24:23,892 --> 01:24:25,792
- Heil Hitler.
- Heil Hitler.

1296
01:24:29,597 --> 01:24:32,259
Come on, quick.

1297
01:24:32,367 --> 01:24:34,335
[Engine Revs]

1298
01:24:40,442 --> 01:24:42,137
Right, man! Right! You're not in England.

1299
01:24:42,243 --> 01:24:44,143
<i>- Oh, I'd forgotten.
- [Vehicle Horn Honks]</i>

1300
01:24:55,457 --> 01:24:57,755
Not much of a life, a secret agent.

1301
01:24:57,859 --> 01:24:59,759
And the pay is bad too, sir.

1302
01:24:59,861 --> 01:25:01,761
<i>[Man Grunts]</i>

1303
01:25:09,370 --> 01:25:11,270
I was just thinking, Charters.

1304
01:25:11,372 --> 01:25:15,399
In the last war, the army took over Lord's
Cricket Ground for drilling troops on.

1305
01:25:17,412 --> 01:25:21,041
- Wonder if they'll do it this time.
- Shortsighted, you know.

1306
01:25:21,149 --> 01:25:23,947
Better pull up here, Charters. We can't
get to Switzerland by any of the main roads.

1307
01:25:24,052 --> 01:25:26,714
Let me take over, will you?

1308
01:25:26,821 --> 01:25:30,689
Age around 22, height 5'4".

1309
01:25:30,792 --> 01:25:34,387
Slim figure, dark, brown eyes.

1310
01:25:36,297 --> 01:25:40,597
That's the lot. Phone these descriptions to
all stations within a hundred-mile radius.

1311
01:25:40,702 --> 01:25:44,297
A report has just come in, sir, that the
car has left the city by the south road.

1312
01:25:44,405 --> 01:25:46,305
So they are making for Switzerland.

1313
01:25:47,542 --> 01:25:49,601
- We take the road.
- Very good.

1314
01:25:58,419 --> 01:26:00,944
There's one thing that's
worrying me, Randall, old man.

1315
01:26:01,055 --> 01:26:03,023
It may be silly of me, of course, but...

1316
01:26:03,124 --> 01:26:05,388
How exactly are we going to
get across the Swiss frontier?

1317
01:26:05,493 --> 01:26:07,461
I know a little place where
I used to go climbing...

1318
01:26:07,562 --> 01:26:09,996
about 8,000 feet up where
Switzerland and Germany meet.

1319
01:26:10,098 --> 01:26:12,191
You're not going to ask us to
hang about on ropes, I hope.

1320
01:26:12,300 --> 01:26:15,895
I'm not, but they may. There's a
narrow road leads right to the top.

1321
01:26:16,004 --> 01:26:18,529
- What's over the top?
- Switzerland.

1322
01:26:18,640 --> 01:26:21,268
- Anything in between?
- 6,000-feet drop.

1323
01:26:21,376 --> 01:26:23,276
- Well, how can we, uh...
- Skip it.

1324
01:26:23,378 --> 01:26:24,845
Skip it?

1325
01:26:24,946 --> 01:26:27,414
[Tires Screeching]

1326
01:26:29,784 --> 01:26:32,514
- There's a car following us!
- Is there? Well, here we go.

1327
01:26:39,294 --> 01:26:41,228
Don't let them get away!

1328
01:26:49,971 --> 01:26:51,233
[Shouting In German]

1329
01:26:51,339 --> 01:26:53,637
<i>[Horn Honking]</i>

1330
01:26:55,910 --> 01:26:58,743
<i>[Air Hissing]</i>

1331
01:27:00,515 --> 01:27:02,483
I'll have to change the wheel!

1332
01:27:33,781 --> 01:27:35,681
Watch the road, Charters.

1333
01:27:35,783 --> 01:27:38,377
Hello! Anybody here? Caldicott.

1334
01:27:38,486 --> 01:27:40,647
Anybody around?

1335
01:27:40,755 --> 01:27:43,189
<i>- Switzerland.
- [Footsteps On Stairs]</i>

1336
01:27:43,291 --> 01:27:45,851
<i>Good morning to you, sir. Good morning.</i>

1337
01:27:45,960 --> 01:27:49,191
<i>- [Bennett] Are you in charge here?
- Yes. There's only me.</i>

1338
01:27:50,231 --> 01:27:52,131
- I want to cross to Switzerland.
- Now, sir?

1339
01:27:52,233 --> 01:27:54,997
- Yes, now.
- But we're at war.

1340
01:27:55,103 --> 01:27:58,561
I had orders yesterday
to close the teleferic.

1341
01:27:58,673 --> 01:28:00,903
My orders come from a higher source.

1342
01:28:01,009 --> 01:28:03,671
Higher than the chief of police at Maxberg?

1343
01:28:03,778 --> 01:28:06,941
- Gestapo headquarters at Munich.
- Oh.

1344
01:28:07,048 --> 01:28:10,279
I have been instructed to show this
lady and gentleman safely out of Germany.

1345
01:28:10,385 --> 01:28:11,875
I better ring Christopher.

1346
01:28:21,129 --> 01:28:22,596
<i>[Attendant] Yes. Right away.</i>

1347
01:28:22,697 --> 01:28:25,757
<i>- There's a car coming. Looks like them.
- There are five of them altogether.</i>

1348
01:28:25,867 --> 01:28:28,461
<i>- Keep an eye on them.
- How are the goats, Christopher?</i>

1349
01:28:28,569 --> 01:28:31,299
Yes, thank you, Christopher.
I got it. And the butter.

1350
01:28:31,406 --> 01:28:33,033
Do you want to be dismissed for incompetence?

1351
01:28:33,141 --> 01:28:35,769
They'll be leaving in about
two minutes, Christopher.

1352
01:28:37,345 --> 01:28:40,508
I shall require to see your papers,
sir. Have you got your passports?

1353
01:28:40,615 --> 01:28:42,515
How long does this take to cross the valley?

1354
01:28:42,617 --> 01:28:45,518
- About four minutes.
- Once it's in midair, can it be stopped?

1355
01:28:45,620 --> 01:28:48,453
Why, yes, sir, if anyone wanted to stop it.

1356
01:28:48,556 --> 01:28:50,581
Will you follow me to the office?

1357
01:28:52,093 --> 01:28:54,061
This way, please.

1358
01:28:55,663 --> 01:28:58,496
- Can you see them?
- No, but I can hear the engine.

1359
01:28:58,599 --> 01:29:00,499
- How does this thing work?
- That shouldn't be difficult.

1360
01:29:00,601 --> 01:29:02,694
- Well, how?
- Yes, obviously, this starts it.

1361
01:29:02,804 --> 01:29:04,271
<i>- Yes?
- [Rounding On Door]</i>

1362
01:29:04,372 --> 01:29:06,499
- Yes. This is the speed regulator.
- Speed regulator, right. Get in quick.

1363
01:29:06,607 --> 01:29:10,134
<i>- All of you! Quick! Caldicott!
- [Rounding Continues]</i>

1364
01:29:10,244 --> 01:29:13,077
- What about you?
- I'll start it and then jump on.

1365
01:29:16,517 --> 01:29:17,916
They're here!

1366
01:29:20,788 --> 01:29:23,348
- Come on. Jump in.
- Yes, but they...
they'll stop us halfway across.

1367
01:29:23,458 --> 01:29:25,426
Get in, will you!

1368
01:29:29,697 --> 01:29:31,790
Come on! Quickly!

1369
01:29:41,042 --> 01:29:43,203
There it is!

